{"title_page": "Michael Lyons (sculptor)", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| honorific_suffix = [[Royal Society of Arts|RSA]] [[Royal Society of Sculptors|FRSS]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = 150px\n| alt              = Michael Lyons Sculptor with Sculptures 2017\n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1943|7|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bilston]], Staffordshire, England\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2019|4|19|1943|7|10|df=7}}\n| death_place      =  [[Cawood, North Yorkshire]], England\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = British \n| residence        = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = Metal sculpture\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| home_town        = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| module           = \n}}\n'''Michael Lyons''' [[Royal Society of Arts|RSA]] [[Royal Society of Sculptors|FRSS]] (10 July 1943 &ndash; 19 April 2019) was a British sculptor who was instrumental in the creation of the [[Yorkshire Sculpture Park]].<ref name='YP'>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/people/michael-lyons-sculptor-1-9731279 |title=Michael Lyons, sculptor |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=27 April 2019 |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref name='ML'>{{cite web |url=http://www.michaellyonssculptor.co.uk/?page_id=6 |title=BIOGRAPHY |publisher=Michael Lyons |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nLyons was educated at [[Cotton College]], Staffordshire, at [[Wolverhampton College of Art]] (1959&ndash;1963), [[Hornsey College of Art]] (1963&ndash;1964) and Newcastle University (1964&ndash;1967).<ref name='CSF'>{{cite web |url=http://www.sculpture.org.uk/artist/michael-lyons |title=Artists: Michael Lyons |publisher=[[Cass Sculpture Foundation]] |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nLyons was Head of Sculpture at the [[Manchester Metropolitan University]] between 1989 and 1993 and also taught at college in the USA, China, and Canada. He represented Britain in [[Biennale]]s in China, Argentina, Mexico and Australia.<ref name='fine108'>{{cite web |url=https://108fineart.com/artists/michael-lyons/ |title= Artist: Michael Lyons |publisher=108 Fine Art |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref> His drawings and sculptures are in various collections, including those of the Canary Wharf Group, Arts Council England, the Henry Moore Institute, and the Yale Centre for British Art.<ref name='YP' />\n\nIn 2011, three sculptures, 'Mayflower', 'Energy Of The Mountain: Echo And Revelation' and 'Energy Of The Mountain' were stolen from Lyons' studio and were never recovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/9229822.scupltures-snatched-from-garden-of-cawood-artist-michael-lyons/|title=Scupltures{{sic|hide=y}} snatched from artist\u2019s garden|website=York Press|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\nHe was a Trustee of the [[Ironbridge Open Air Museum of Steel Sculpture]].<ref name='fine108' />\n\n===Exhibitions===\nLyons has exhibited at various galleries, shows, and venues including:\n*[[New School House Gallery]]: 'Half-light' (19 June 2015&ndash;15 August 2015).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.artrabbit.com/events/michael-lyons-39half-light39 |title=Exhibition: Michael Lyons. 'Half-light' (19 June 2015&ndash;15 August 2015) |publisher=New School House Gallery |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Leeds Art Gallery]]. 'Michael Lyons: Freeze Frame' (9 March 2016&ndash; 26 July 2016).<ref>{{Cite book |editor1=Judith LeGrove |title=Michael Lyons: Freeze Frame  |ISBN=978-1-908326-34-8 |publisher=University of Leeds}}</ref>\n*[[One Canada Square]] ''Scale Appropriate'' on loan (31 March 2014&ndash; 23 May 2014).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://group.canarywharf.com/media/press-releases/michael-lyons-striking-steel-sculpture-comes-to-life-at-canary-wharf-2/ |title=Michael Lyons\u2019 Striking Steel Sculpture Comes to Life at Canary Wharf |date=27 February 2014 |publisher=Canary Wharf Group PLC |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n*Yorkshire Sculpture Park.<ref name='CSF' /> \n*Macay Museo de Arte Contemporaneo.<ref name='CSF' />\n*[[York Art Gallery]] / [[York Museum Gardens]] ''Michael Lyons: Ancient and Modern'' (25 May 2019&ndash;May 2020).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/17663075.sculptures-by-artist-michael-lyons-go-on-display-at-york-art-gallery/ |title=Sculptures by artist Michael Lyons go on display at York Art Gallery |author1=Laycock, M |date=25 May 2019 |newspaper=York Press}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1966, he featured in the [[New Contemporaries|Young Contemporaries]] in London and won a Peter Stuyvesant Prize at the 1967 Northern Young Contemporaries in Manchester. In 2006 he won the ''Premio Fondo Nacional de las Artes'' at Chaco Biennale, Argentina.<ref name='CSF' />\n\nIn 1994 he was elected as a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] and as a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Sculptors]].<ref name='ML' /> He had also served as Vice-President of the RSS from 1994&ndash;1997.<ref name='YP' />  Lyons was also an Honorary member of the Manchester Academy of Fine Arts.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Michael Lyons Geograph-1414814-by-Sue-Adair.jpg|''Doves of Peace'' at [[The People's History Museum]]\nFile:Michael Lyons Geograph-1722583-by-David-Smith.jpg|''Argonaut 1909''' \nFile:Sonidos de viento.jpg|At the Argentinia Bienalle, 2006\nFile:Michael Lyons \"Michaelmas\" 1983.jpg|''Michaelmas'' (1983) in the [[York Museum Gardens]], 2019\nFile:Michael Lyons \"Harvest Demeter's Dream\" 2000.jpg|''Harvest: Demeter's Dream'' (2000) in the York Museum Gardens, 2019\nFile:Mayflower, 1983 (3).jpg|''Mayflower'' (1983) in the grounds of [[York Art Gallery]], 2019\nFile:Michael Lyons - Michaelmas.jpg|''Michaelmas'' (1982) in the York Museum Gardens, 2019\n</gallery>\n\n== Personal life ==\nLyons grew up in the [[Black Country]], and the area\u2019s post-war industrial landscape had a life-long influence on his work, as did his strong [[Catholic church|Catholic]] upbringing and, in later life, his interest in [[mythology]] and [[cosmology]].{{citation needed |date=August 2019}} In 1970 he married Stephanie Kay, whom he had met while they were students in the Department of Fine Art at Newcastle University and together they had a son David born in 1975 and daughter Anna in 1978.{{citation needed |date=August 2019}} In 1977 he moved to [[Cawood]], near [[York]] where he established a studio.{{citation needed |date=August 2019}}\n\n==Legacy==\nIn Lyon's Obituary in the Yorkshire Post, [[Peter Murray (Yorkshire Sculpture Park)|Peter Murray]] wrote: \u201cHis drawings often portrayed a sensitive response to landscape which had a strong influence on his powerful sculptures, which looked at home in the landscape.\u201d<ref name='YP' />\n\nIn an obituary in the Guardian he was described as: \"...one of the group of artists who developed successful careers from a non-metropolitan base. Such strength of mind was the driving force that Michael and others, principally Peter Murray, engaged to create the Yorkshire Sculpture Park in 1977...so many young artists rushed off to London, and lost immediate connection with land and sky. It is this vision that Michael instinctively wound into his sculpture, while Yorkshire also gave him \u201cthe freedom to cut metal and smoke cigars\u201d\"<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2019/jun/12/michael-lyons-obituary|title=Michael Lyons obituary|last=Hamilton|first=James|date=2019-06-12|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Michael Lyons'' by Peter Murray, David Sweet, Michael Lyons, [exhibition catalogue], Yorkshire Sculpture Park (1998)\n*''Close encounters of the three-dimensional kind: an experiential biography of Michael Lyons'' by Judith LeGrove, Green Bronze IV (1980), unpublished (winner of the 2010 Henry Moore Institute MA essay prize)\n*''Scale Appropriate'' by Ann Elliott, catalogue essay for exhibition at Canary Wharf (2014)\n*''The Sculpture of Michael Lyons'' by Judith LeGrove, Sansom & Co, (30 May 2013) (Hardback, 2013) {{ISBN|978-1908326348}}\n*''Natural causes: the sculpture of Michael Lyons'' by David Sweet, Sculpture Journal, 22.2 (2013)\n*''Michael Lyons: from Bilston to Beijing'' by Judith LeGrove, SculpturesPacific, 11 (2015)\n*''Half-Light'' Michael Lyons and Judith LeGrove, (catalogue for exhibition at New School House Gallery, York, 2015)\n*''The Sculpture of Michael Lyons by Judith LeGrove'' by James Hamilton, [book review], Sculpture Journal Vol. 24.1 (2015)\n*''Freeze Frame'' catalogue edited by Dr .Judith LeGrove. Includes three essays: \u2018Freeze Frame\u2019 by Dr.Judith LeGrove; \u2018Drawn to Sculpture: Michael Lyons\u2019 \u2018Lenten Cover\u2019 (1979)\u2019 by Michael Howard; and \u2018Michael Lyons: Natural and Industrial ca 1963 -70\u2019 by Dr.Julia Kelley (2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.leeds.ac.uk/product-catalogue/art-gallery/leeds-university-library-galleries/books-and-catalogues/michael-lyons-freeze-frame|title=Michael Lyons: Freeze Frame {{!}} University of Leeds|website=store.leeds.ac.uk|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n*''Future Now'' -100 Contemporary Artists from the Aesthetical Art Prize, published in association with Aesthetica Magazine (2016)\n*''Machines, Myths and Murder'' by William Varley  review of \u2018Machines and Myths\u2019 in \u2018The Jackdaw'(2018) \n*''David Sweet on Michael Lyons: Machines and Myths, Exhibition Review (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://instantloveland.com/wp/2018/12/05/david-sweet-on-michael-lyons-machines-and-myths/|title=David Sweet on Michael Lyons: Machines and Myths|date=2018-12-05|website=Instantloveland|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>''\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.henry-moore.org/archives-and-library/sculpture-research-library/artists-lives-project/michael-lyons Lyons describes a trip to see Brancusi's 'Endless Column' in Romania (Henry Moore Institute)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lyons, Michael}}\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:British sculptors]]\n[[Category:People from Bilston]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Newcastle University]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| honorific_suffix = [[Royal Society of Arts|RSA]] [[Royal Society of Sculptors|FRSS]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = 150px\n| alt              = Michael Lyons Sculptor with Sculptures 2017\n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1943|7|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bilston]], Staffordshire, England\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2019|4|19|1943|7|10|df=7}}\n| death_place      =  [[Cawood, North Yorkshire]], England\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = British \n| residence        = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = Metal sculpture\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| home_town        = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| module           = \n}}\n'''Michael Lyons''' [[Royal Society of Arts|RSA]] [[Royal Society of Sculptors|FRSS]] (10 July 1943 &ndash; 19 April 2019) was a British sculptor who was instrumental in the creation of the [[Yorkshire Sculpture Park]].<ref name='YP'>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/people/michael-lyons-sculptor-1-9731279 |title=Michael Lyons, sculptor |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=27 April 2019 |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref name='ML'>{{cite web |url=http://www.michaellyonssculptor.co.uk/?page_id=6 |title=BIOGRAPHY |publisher=Michael Lyons |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nLyons was educated at [[Cotton College]], Staffordshire, at [[Wolverhampton College of Art]] (1959&ndash;1963), [[Hornsey College of Art]] (1963&ndash;1964) and Newcastle University (1964&ndash;1967).<ref name='CSF'>{{cite web |url=http://www.sculpture.org.uk/artist/michael-lyons |title=Artists: Michael Lyons |publisher=[[Cass Sculpture Foundation]] |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nLyons was Head of Sculpture at the [[Manchester Metropolitan University]] between 1989 and 1993 and also taught at college in the USA, China, and Canada. He represented Britain in [[Biennale]]s in China, Argentina, Mexico and Australia.<ref name='fine108'>{{cite web |url=https://108fineart.com/artists/michael-lyons/ |title= Artist: Michael Lyons |publisher=108 Fine Art |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref> His drawings and sculptures are in various collections, including those of the Canary Wharf Group, Arts Council England, the Henry Moore Institute, and the Yale Centre for British Art.<ref name='YP' />\n\nIn 2011, three sculptures, 'Mayflower', 'Energy Of The Mountain: Echo And Revelation' and 'Energy Of The Mountain' were stolen from Lyons' studio and were never recovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/9229822.scupltures-snatched-from-garden-of-cawood-artist-michael-lyons/|title=Scupltures snatched from artist\u2019s garden|website=York Press|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\nHe was a Trustee of the [[Ironbridge Open Air Museum of Steel Sculpture]].<ref name='fine108' />\n\n===Exhibitions===\nLyons has exhibited at various galleries, shows, and venues including:\n*[[New School House Gallery]]: 'Half-light' (19 June 2015&ndash;15 August 2015).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.artrabbit.com/events/michael-lyons-39half-light39 |title=Exhibition: Michael Lyons. 'Half-light' (19 June 2015&ndash;15 August 2015) |publisher=New School House Gallery |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Leeds Art Gallery]]. 'Michael Lyons: Freeze Frame' (9 March 2016&ndash; 26 July 2016).<ref>{{Cite book |editor1=Judith LeGrove |title=Michael Lyons: Freeze Frame  |ISBN=978-1-908326-34-8 |publisher=University of Leeds}}</ref>\n*[[One Canada Square]] ''Scale Appropriate'' on loan (31 March 2014&ndash; 23 May 2014).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://group.canarywharf.com/media/press-releases/michael-lyons-striking-steel-sculpture-comes-to-life-at-canary-wharf-2/ |title=Michael Lyons\u2019 Striking Steel Sculpture Comes to Life at Canary Wharf |date=27 February 2014 |publisher=Canary Wharf Group PLC |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n*Yorkshire Sculpture Park.<ref name='CSF' /> \n*Macay Museo de Arte Contemporaneo.<ref name='CSF' />\n*[[York Art Gallery]] / [[York Museum Gardens]] ''Michael Lyons: Ancient and Modern'' (25 May 2019&ndash;May 2020).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/17663075.sculptures-by-artist-michael-lyons-go-on-display-at-york-art-gallery/ |title=Sculptures by artist Michael Lyons go on display at York Art Gallery |author1=Laycock, M |date=25 May 2019 |newspaper=York Press}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1966, he featured in the [[New Contemporaries|Young Contemporaries]] in London and won a Peter Stuyvesant Prize at the 1967 Northern Young Contemporaries in Manchester. In 2006 he won the ''Premio Fondo Nacional de las Artes'' at Chaco Biennale, Argentina.<ref name='CSF' />\n\nIn 1994 he was elected as a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] and as a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Sculptors]].<ref name='ML' /> He had also served as Vice-President of the RSS from 1994&ndash;1997.<ref name='YP' />  Lyons was also an Honorary member of the Manchester Academy of Fine Arts.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Michael Lyons Geograph-1414814-by-Sue-Adair.jpg|''Doves of Peace'' at [[The People's History Museum]]\nFile:Michael Lyons Geograph-1722583-by-David-Smith.jpg|''Argonaut 1909''' \nFile:Sonidos de viento.jpg|At the Argentinia Bienalle, 2006\nFile:Michael Lyons \"Michaelmas\" 1983.jpg|''Michaelmas'' (1983) in the [[York Museum Gardens]], 2019\nFile:Michael Lyons \"Harvest Demeter's Dream\" 2000.jpg|''Harvest: Demeter's Dream'' (2000) in the York Museum Gardens, 2019\nFile:Mayflower, 1983 (3).jpg|''Mayflower'' (1983) in the grounds of [[York Art Gallery]], 2019\nFile:Michael Lyons - Michaelmas.jpg|''Michaelmas'' (1982) in the York Museum Gardens, 2019\n</gallery>\n\n== Personal life ==\nLyons grew up in the [[Black Country]], and the area\u2019s post-war industrial landscape had a life-long influence on his work, as did his strong [[Catholic church|Catholic]] upbringing and, in later life, his interest in [[mythology]] and [[cosmology]].{{citation needed |date=August 2019}} In 1970 he married Stephanie Kay, whom he had met while they were students in the Department of Fine Art at Newcastle University and together they had a son David born in 1975 and daughter Anna in 1978.{{citation needed |date=August 2019}} In 1977 he moved to [[Cawood]], near [[York]] where he established a studio.{{citation needed |date=August 2019}}\n\n==Legacy==\nIn Lyon's Obituary in the Yorkshire Post, [[Peter Murray (Yorkshire Sculpture Park)|Peter Murray]] wrote: \u201cHis drawings often portrayed a sensitive response to landscape which had a strong influence on his powerful sculptures, which looked at home in the landscape.\u201d<ref name='YP' />\n\nIn an obituary in the Guardian he was described as: \"...one of the group of artists who developed successful careers from a non-metropolitan base. Such strength of mind was the driving force that Michael and others, principally Peter Murray, engaged to create the Yorkshire Sculpture Park in 1977...so many young artists rushed off to London, and lost immediate connection with land and sky. It is this vision that Michael instinctively wound into his sculpture, while Yorkshire also gave him \u201cthe freedom to cut metal and smoke cigars\u201d\"<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2019/jun/12/michael-lyons-obituary|title=Michael Lyons obituary|last=Hamilton|first=James|date=2019-06-12|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Michael Lyons'' by Peter Murray, David Sweet, Michael Lyons, [exhibition catalogue], Yorkshire Sculpture Park (1998)\n*''Close encounters of the three-dimensional kind: an experiential biography of Michael Lyons'' by Judith LeGrove, Green Bronze IV (1980), unpublished (winner of the 2010 Henry Moore Institute MA essay prize)\n*''Scale Appropriate'' by Ann Elliott, catalogue essay for exhibition at Canary Wharf (2014)\n*''The Sculpture of Michael Lyons'' by Judith LeGrove, Sansom & Co, (30 May 2013) (Hardback, 2013) {{ISBN|978-1908326348}}\n*''Natural causes: the sculpture of Michael Lyons'' by David Sweet, Sculpture Journal, 22.2 (2013)\n*''Michael Lyons: from Bilston to Beijing'' by Judith LeGrove, SculpturesPacific, 11 (2015)\n*''Half-Light'' Michael Lyons and Judith LeGrove, (catalogue for exhibition at New School House Gallery, York, 2015)\n*''The Sculpture of Michael Lyons by Judith LeGrove'' by James Hamilton, [book review], Sculpture Journal Vol. 24.1 (2015)\n*''Freeze Frame'' catalogue edited by Dr .Judith LeGrove. Includes three essays: \u2018Freeze Frame\u2019 by Dr.Judith LeGrove; \u2018Drawn to Sculpture: Michael Lyons\u2019 \u2018Lenten Cover\u2019 (1979)\u2019 by Michael Howard; and \u2018Michael Lyons: Natural and Industrial ca 1963 -70\u2019 by Dr.Julia Kelley (2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.leeds.ac.uk/product-catalogue/art-gallery/leeds-university-library-galleries/books-and-catalogues/michael-lyons-freeze-frame|title=Michael Lyons: Freeze Frame {{!}} University of Leeds|website=store.leeds.ac.uk|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n*''Future Now'' -100 Contemporary Artists from the Aesthetical Art Prize, published in association with Aesthetica Magazine (2016)\n*''Machines, Myths and Murder'' by William Varley  review of \u2018Machines and Myths\u2019 in \u2018The Jackdaw'(2018) \n*''David Sweet on Michael Lyons: Machines and Myths, Exhibition Review (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://instantloveland.com/wp/2018/12/05/david-sweet-on-michael-lyons-machines-and-myths/|title=David Sweet on Michael Lyons: Machines and Myths|date=2018-12-05|website=Instantloveland|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>''\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.henry-moore.org/archives-and-library/sculpture-research-library/artists-lives-project/michael-lyons Lyons describes a trip to see Brancusi's 'Endless Column' in Romania (Henry Moore Institute)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lyons, Michael}}\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:British sculptors]]\n[[Category:People from Bilston]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Newcastle University]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Lyons_(sculptor)"}
{"title_page": "Worms (1995 video game)", "text_new": "{{About||the 2007 game|Worms (2007 video game)|the 1983 game|Worms?}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{under construction|placedby=KGRAMR|nosection=yes}}\n{{in use}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title        = Worms\n| image        = Worms-win-cover.jpg\n| image_size   = 256px\n| caption      = \n| developer    = [[Team17]]\n| publisher    = [[Ocean Software]]\n| designer     = [[Andy Davidson (game designer)|Andy Davidson]]\n|composer      = [[Bj\u00f8rn Lynne]]\n| series       = ''[[Worms (series)|Worms]]''\n| engine       = \n| released     = '''Amiga, CD32, Game Boy & Mac'''<br />{{vgrelease|EU|1995<ref>{{MobyGames|id=/worms|name=''Worms''}}</ref><ref>[http://amr.abime.net/review_10209 Worms review from CU Amiga Magazine (Dec 1995) \u2013 Amiga Magazine Rack] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220093731/http://amr.abime.net/review_10209 |date=2012-02-20 }}</ref>}}'''Mega Drive'''<br />{{vgrelease|EU|June 1, 1995}}'''PC (DOS)'''<br />{{Video game release|NA|October 31, 1995 (Retail)|EU|1995|NA|October 19, 2011 (Steam)}}'''PlayStation'''<br />{{Video game release|NA|1996|EU|November, 1995<ref name=\"CTW565\">{{cite magazine |title=Christmas Games Guide |magazine=Computer Trade Weekly |location=United Kingdom |date=27 November 1995 |issue=565 |page=43 }}</ref>|JP|February 28, 1997}}'''SNES'''<br />{{vgrelease|EU|September 29, 1996}}'''Saturn'''<br />{{Video game release|NA|1996|EU|1995|JP|March 14, 1997}}'''Jaguar'''<br />{{vgrelease|NA|May 15, 1998}}\n| genre        = [[Artillery game|Artillery]], [[Strategy video game|Strategy]]\n| modes        = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n| platforms    = [[Amiga]], [[Amiga CD32]], [[Game Boy]], [[Sega Genesis]], [[Atari Jaguar]], [[Mac OS]], [[IBM PC compatible]] ([[MS-DOS]]), [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[Sega Saturn]], [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]]\n}}\n'''''Worms''''' is a 2D [[Artillery game|artillery]] [[Strategy video game|tactical]] video game developed by [[Team17]] and released in [[1995 in video gaming|1995]]. It is the first game in the [[Worms (series)|''Worms series'']] of video games.\n\n''Worms'' is a [[turn based]] game where a player controls a team of worms against other teams of worms that are controlled by a computer or human opponent. The aim is to use various weapons to kill the worms on the other teams and have the last surviving worm(s).\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[Image:Worms scrapyardscreenshot.png|thumb|left|From the [[Amiga]] version: A [[scrapyard]] themed level, with the player using the [[blowtorch]] tool.]]\n''Worms'' is a turn based [[artillery game]], similar to other early games in the genre such as ''[[Scorched Earth (video game)|Scorched Earth]].\nEach player controls a team of several worms. During the course of the game, players take turns selecting one of their worms. They then use whatever tools and weapons are available to attack and kill the opponents' worms, thereby winning the game. Worms may move around the terrain in a variety of ways, normally by walking and jumping but also by using particular tools such as the \"Bungee\" and \"Ninja Rope\", to move to otherwise inaccessible areas. Each turn is time-limited to ensure that players do not hold up the game with excessive thinking or moving. The time limit can be modified in some of the games in the Worms series.\n\nOver fifty weapons and tools may be available each time a game is played, and differing selections of weapons and tools can be saved into a \"scheme\" for easy selection in future games. Other scheme settings allow options such as deployment of reinforcement crates, from which additional weapons can be obtained, and sudden death where the game is rushed to a conclusion after a time limit expires. Some settings provide for the inclusion of objects such as land mines and explosive barrels.\n\nWhen most weapons are used, they cause explosions that deform the terrain, creating circular cavities. If a worm is hit with a weapon, they will lose health. A worm who is out of health will die by blowing themselves up and leaving a grave marker. Worms can also die by being thrown off the side of the map or by falling into the water at the map's base.\n\n== Development ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThe game was originally created by Andy Davidson as an entry for a [[Blitz BASIC]] programming competition run by the ''[[Amiga Format]]'' magazine, a cut-down version of the [[programming language]] having been covermounted previously. The game at this stage was called '''''Total Wormage''''' (possibly in reference to ''[[Total Carnage]]'') and it did not win the competition. Davidson sent the game to several publishers with no success. He then took the game to the [[European Computer Trade Show]], where he met with Mark Foreman \u2013 Head Games Buyer at GEM Distribution. Mark suggested to Andy that he should speak to Ocean/Team17 as they would be an ideal partner \u2013 they also had a stand at the show. Team17 made an offer on-the-spot to develop and publish the game.<ref>IGN [ Worms Blast Preview]</ref><ref>GameSpy [ Worms: Open Warfare Developer Diary]</ref>\n\nThe references to the developers' home county, [[Yorkshire]], is visible, with a soundbank named \"Tykes\", which is a Yorkshire accent, and in the \"Hell\" level found in the single player mission mode, a sign with \"Welcome to [[Ossett]]! Ha! ha! ha!\" written on it.\n===Character, level and sound design===\nThe game's graphics and sound design is primarily 'cartoon-like' (though less so than the later games in the series). Levels designs are randomly generated by the use of alpha-numeric strings as their [[Random seed|seeds]]. The object and landscape sets used to generate the field are arranged into 'themes' including forests, martian landscapes, beaches and 'hell'.\n\n== Release ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThe North American release of the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] version was the subject of considerable negotiation, as Sony Computer Entertainment of America had a policy against 2D games being published for the console.<ref name=\"NGenPSw\"/> The [[Sega Saturn]] version of the game was a straight port of the PlayStation version.<ref name=\"SSMukSSw\"/>\n\nAn [[Atari Jaguar]] version was also developed by Team17 and published by [[Telegames]] in May 15, 1998.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Charlton|first=Frank|url=http://www.stformat.com/stf85/pages_nx1500/stf85_010.jpg|title=STF News... - Worms wriggles in|magazine=[[ST Format]]|issue=85|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=August 1996|page=10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Jason|url=http://www.jaguarsector.com/index.php?autocom=ibwiki&cmd=article&do=print_article&id=379|title=Atari Jaguar Timeline|website=jaguarsector.com|accessdate=2018-09-13|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130629025431/http://www.jaguarsector.com/index.php?autocom=ibwiki&cmd=article&do=print_article&id=379|archivedate=29 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Telegames announced the release of this version after becoming the last remaining software publisher for the Jaguar and like other games published following the system's discontinuation,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3AEGM_US_094.pdf&page=24|title=Tidbits...|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=94|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=May 1997|page=24}}</ref> ''Worms'' could be purchased either through [[Direct selling|direct order]] from Telegames' US and UK websites or select retailers such as [[EB Games|Electronics Boutique]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:GamePro_US_105.pdf&page=22|title=News Bits|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=105|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=June 1997|page=20}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/stream/Gamefan_Vol_5_Issue_10#page/n41|title=Recent Sightings of an Endangered Species|magazine=[[GameFan]]|volume=5|issue=10|publisher=Shinno Media|date=October 1997|page=36}}</ref> It also served as the final title released for the console to be officially licensed with the Atari name, as the rights to said name and other [[intellectual property]] rights of [[Atari Corporation]] were sold to [[Hasbro Interactive]] before [[JT Storage]]'s bankruptcy in [[1999 in video gaming|1999]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.host.fptoday.com/melek/jaguar/jag-96.htm|title=Hasbro Interactive Acquires Legendary Atari Game Property Assets|website=Nine Lives|date=March 16, 1998|accessdate=2018-12-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051107232949/http://www.host.fptoday.com/melek/jaguar/jag-96.htm|archivedate=7 November 2005|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Cancelled ports ===\nIn 1995, Team17 began development on a port of ''Worms'' to [[Nintendo]]'s [[Virtual Boy]] platform.<ref name=\"MMan\u00edav3i8\">{{cite magazine|author=|url=https://archive.org/stream/MicromaniaTerceraEpocaSpanishIssue8#page/n57/mode/1up|title=Reportaje: Extra\u00f1a mezcla... de gusanos - Worms|magazine=[[Microman\u00eda]]|volume=3|issue=8|publisher=HobbyPress|date=September 1995|page=58|lang=es}}</ref> The game was to be published by Ocean, but was canceled only weeks into development as a result of Nintendo's discontinuation of the console.<ref>{{cite web|last=Radke|first=Christian|url=https://www.planetvb.com/modules/games/?u030g|title=Worms|website=planetvb.com|date=2020|access-date=2020-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529195248/https://www.planetvb.com/modules/games/?u030g|archive-date=2019-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[32X]] release was also planned but never released as well.<ref name=\"MMan\u00edav3i8\"/>\n\n=== Expansion pack ===\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n''Worms Reinforcements'' ([[1996 in video gaming|1996]]) is an expansion pack for ''Worms'', which was later amalgamated with the original game to create ''Worms and Reinforcements United'' (a.k.a. ''Worms United'' or ''Worms Utd.'') the same year. Released only for the [[personal computer|PC]], it added a single player campaign and the ability to add custom levels and soundpacks (which was already available for the [[Amiga]] version). It also included an introductory FMV.\n\n=== Director's cut ===\n{{seealso|Worms: The Director's Cut}}\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n''Worms: The Director's Cut'' ([[1997 in video gaming|1997]]) is a sequel to ''Worms'', available only on the Amiga. It is largely built upon the original Amiga game engine with various gameplay enhancement and additions, as well as graphical improvements and fixes. During the development of ''Worms 2'', Andy Davidson wrote this special edition produced exclusively for the AGA chipset Amiga. Only 5000 copies were ever sold. It was also the last version released for the Commodore Amiga platform from which the game originated.\n\n=== Remake ===\n{{seealso|Worms (2007 video game)}}\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nA [[Video game remake|remake]], also called ''[[Worms (2007 video game)|Worms]]'', for the Xbox 360 was released in 2007. It has since been released to the PS3, in April 2009, and on the [[iPhone]] on July 11, 2009.\n\n== Reception ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; font-size:80%; text-align:center; margin:1em; margin-top:0; padding:0; background:none;\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n! colspan=10 style=\"font-size: 100%\" | Reception\n|-\n! colspan=10 | Aggregate scores\n|-\n! rowspan=2  | Aggregator\n! colspan=10 | Scores\n|-\n! [[Amiga]]\n! [[Amiga CD32|CD32]]\n! [[Sega Mega Drive|SMD]]\n! [[Personal computer|PC]]\n! [[PlayStation (console)|PS]]\n! [[Sega Saturn|SS]]\n! [[Game Boy|GB]]\n! [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]]\n! [[Atari Jaguar|Jaguar]]\n|-\n| ''[[GameRankings]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 40%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/926446-worms/index.html|title=Worms for Genesis|work=[[GameRankings]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=2019|access-date=2020-04-15|archive-url