mpany|Birmingham Railway Carriage & Wagon Co.]]\n|-\n|CLCo\n|[[Cammell Laird|Cammell Laird & Co. Ltd.]]\n|-\n|GRCW\n|[[Gloucester Railway Carriage and Wagon Company|Gloucester Railway Carriage & Wagon Co.]]\n|-\n|Leeds\n|[[Leeds Forge Company]]\n|-\n|MCCW\n|[[Metro Cammell|Metropolitan-Cammell Carriage & Wagon Company Ltd.]]\n|-\n|MCWF\n|[[Metro Cammell|Metropolitan Carriage, Wagon & Finance Co.]]\n|-\n|UCC\n|[[Union Construction Company]] (\"Feltham\")\n|}\n|}\n\n== Preservation ==\nSeveral vehicles have been preserved:{{sfn |Hardy |2002 |p=112}} <!-- page no needs checking&nbsp;\u2014 might be total pages. I think this is a later edition of Hardy -->\n{|\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Number<ref group=T>First number is last number assigned when in passenger service; second number is IoW fleet number (2\u201349) or LT service stock number (L13x locomotives or PC85x personnel carriers).</ref>\n!Type\n!Built\n!Builder\n!Location\n|-align=center\n|3327\n|\u2014\n|DM\n|1927\n|MCCW\n|align=left|[[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum, Acton Depot]]\n|-align=center\n|3370\n|L134\n|DM\n|1927\n|MCCW\n|align=left|[[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum, Acton Depot]]\n|-align=center\n|3693\n|L131\n|DM\n|1927\n|MCCW\n|align=left|[[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum, Acton Depot]]\n|-align=center\n|5279\n|27\n|CT\n|1925\n|MCCW\n|align=left|[[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum, Acton Depot]]\n|-align=center\n|7296\n|49\n|T\n|1923\n|CLCo\n|align=left|[[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum, Acton Depot]]\n|}\n|colspan=15 valign=\"top\"|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Key to Type\n|-\n!align=center|CT\n|nowrap|Control Trailer\n|-\n!align=center|DM\n|Driving Motor\n|-\n!align=center|T\n|Trailer\n|}\n|}\n{{Reflist|group=T}}\nFour cars owned by the London Transport Museum have been formed into a four-car unit, consisting of DM 3370, DM 3693, CT 5279 and T 7296 at their Acton Depot. They are awaiting restoration.\n\nSeveral cars that were preserved have since been scrapped.\n* DM 3209 / 7 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4795 |title=3209 Standard Stock Driving Motor |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* DM 3690 / L130 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4730 |title=London Electric 3690 Standard stock driving motor |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* DM 3701 / L135 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4731 |title=London Electric 3701 Standard stock driving motor |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* DM 3706 / 2 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4797 |title=3706 Standard Stock Driving Motor |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* T 7061 / PC850 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4732 |title=London Electric 7061 Trailer car |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* T 7063 / PC851 scrapped at Acton Works 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4733 |title=London Electric 7063 Trailer car |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* T 7071 / PC855 scrapped at Acton Works 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4734 |title=London Electric 7071 Trailer car |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* T 7281 / 44 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3283 |title=Underground Electric Railways 7281 1923 Tube Stock |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n  |first=J Graeme|last=Bruce\n  |title=Tube Trains Under London\n  |publisher=London Transport Board\n  |year=1968\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n  |first=J Graeme|last=Bruce\n  |title=Workhorses of the London Underground\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=1987\n  |isbn=0-904711-87-0\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n  |first=J Graeme|last=Bruce\n  |title=The London Underground Tube Stock\n  |publisher=Ian Allan and London Transport Museum\n  |location=Shepperton\n  |year=1988\n  |isbn=978-0-7110-1707-8\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Stephen |last=Halliday\n  |title=Underground to Everywhere\n  |publisher=The History Press\n  |year=2013\n  |location=Stroud\n  |isbn=978-0-7524-9772-3\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=London Underground Rolling Stock\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=1976\n  |edition=1st\n  |location=London\n  |isbn=978-0-904711-01-1\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=L.P.T.B Rolling Stock 1933-1948\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |publisher=D Bradford Barton\n  |year=1981\n  |isbn=978-0-85153-436-7\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=Standard Tube Stock Part 1: 1922-1945\n  |publisher=London Underground Railway Society\n  |work=Underground\n  |issue=14\n  |year=1986\n  |issn=0306-8609\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last= Hardy\n  |title=Underground Train File: Tube Stock 1933-1959\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=2001\n  |location=London\n  |isbn=978-1-85414-235-1\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=London Underground Rolling Stock\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=2002\n  |edition=15th\n  |location=London\n  |isbn=978-1-85414-263-4\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=Tube Trains on the Isle of Wight\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=2003\n  |location=London\n  |isbn=978-1-85414-276-4\n  |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |year=1983\n  |title=\"Standard\" Tube Stock (A Photographic History) Part 1: 1922\u20131945\n  |periodical=Underground\n  |location=Hemel Hempstead, Hertfordshire\n  |publisher=London Underground Railway Society\n  |issue=14\n  |issn=0306-8609\n  }}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=\"Standard\" Tube Stock (A Photographic History) Part 2 \u2013 1945 Onwards\n  |publisher=London Underground Railway Society\n  |year=1987\n  |location = Hemel Hempstead, Hertfordshire\n  |isbn=978-1-870324-15-1\n  }}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=Underground Train File: Tube Stock 1933-1959\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=2001\n  |location=London\n  |isbn=978-1-85414-235-1\n  }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/collections/collections-online/photographs London Transport Museum Photographic Archive]\n** {{ltmcollection|g2/i0000eg2.jpg|Standard Stock trains at Morden Depot, 1938}}\n** {{ltmcollection|ob/i00005ob.jpg|Standard Stock train at Hammersmith, 1935}}\n** {{ltmcollection|mm/i00009mm.jpg|Standard Stock trailer car at Waterloo, 1936}}\n** {{ltmcollection|ms/i0000ams.jpg|Interior view of Standard Stock car, 1935}}\n\n{{London Underground Rolling Stock}}\n{{Bakerloo line navbox}}\n{{Central line navbox}}\n{{Northern line navbox}}\n{{Piccadilly line navbox}}\n\n[[Category:London Underground electric multiple units|1923]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan Cammell multiple units]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 1923]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox train\n|name         = London Underground Standard Stock\n|image        = File:Hendon Central station, underground railway above ground (CJ Allen, Steel Highway, 1928).jpg\n|image_size   = 300px\n|caption      = Standard stock at Hendon Central, on today's Northern line\n|manufacturer = {{ubl|[[Birmingham Railway Carriage and Wagon Company|Birmingham RC&W Co.]]|[[Cammell Laird]]|[[Union Construction Company]]|[[Gloucester Railway Carriage and Wagon Company|Gloucester RC&W Co.]]|[[Leeds Forge Company]]|[[Metro Cammell]]}}\n|service      = {{ubl|1923-1964 (London Transport)|1967-1989 (Isle of Wight)}}\n|family       =\n|replaced     =\n|lines        = [[Bakerloo line]]<br>[[Central line (London Underground)|Central line]]<br>[[Northern line]]<br>[[Piccadilly line]]\n|carlength    =\n|trainlength  =\n|width        =\n|height       =\n|maxspeed     =\n|weight       =\n|seating      =\n|stocktype    = [[London Underground infrastructure#Subsurface versus deep-level tube lines|Deep-level tube]]\n|notes        = {{Portal-inline|size=tiny|London transport}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Standard Stock''' title was applied to a variety of Tube stock built between 1923 and 1934, all of which shared the same basic characteristics, but with some detailed differences. This design is also sometimes referred to as '''1923 Tube Stock''' or '''Pre 1938 Stock'''. Most of the Standard Stock was built to replace the first generation of [[London Underground Gate Stock|\"Gate Stock\"]] Tube trains or to provide additional trains for extensions built in the 1920s and early 1930s.\nStandard Stock cars consisted of motor cars (with a driver's cab, behind which was a \"switch compartment\" occupying approximately one-third of the length of the car), plus trailer cars and \"control trailers\" (with a driving cab but no motor). All were equipped with air operated sliding doors, although the guard's door on the earlier trains was a manually operated inward-opening hinged door.\n\n==1922 Stock prototype cars==\n\nFor evaluation purposes, in anticipation of the large number of cars that were to be built over the next several years, six experimental cars were ordered and had been delivered by February 1923. There were five trailers and one control trailer, which were marshalled between French-built [[London Underground Gate Stock|\"Gate Stock\"]] driving motor cars. A demonstration for the press took place on the Piccadilly line on 3 February 1923, after which the new cars and the French motor cars were moved by road to the Hampstead Line, entering service in August.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=53}} The French motor cars were part of a batch of 20 which had been rebuilt with air-operated doors, to allow them to work with the [[London Underground 1920 Stock|1920 Stock]], the first batch of vehicles built with air doors.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=49}} The trailers and French motor cars formed the inaugural train on the Hampstead Line extension from Golders Green to Hendon when it opened on 19 November 1923.{{sfn |Bruce |1968 |pp=44\u201345}}\n\nThe builders were given a partial specification, which ensured that each car would have 48 seats and two sets of air-operated double doors on each side, providing an opening which was {{convert|4.5|ft|m|3}} wide. Beyond these basic guidelines, each builder was allowed to build a trailer car to its own design, although externally, they looked very similar. The control trailer was designed by the [[Underground Electric Railways Company of London|Underground Electric Railways]].{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=53}}\nThe stock became known as the 1922 Stock or Competition Stock and was considered part of the Standard stock fleet.{{sfn |Hardy |2001 |p=54}}\n\n== Production stock ==\n[[File:London Underground tube coach (CJ Allen, Steel Highway, 1928).jpg|Interior|thumb]]\n[[File:London Underground Standard Stock - Flickr - James E. Petts (1).jpg|Switch compartment|thumb]]\nThe earliest Standard Stock was built for use on the [[Charing Cross, Euston and Hampstead Railway|Hampstead tube]], which was extended from [[Golders Green tube station|Golders Green]] to [[Edgware tube station|Edgware]] and from Clapham Common to [[Morden tube station|Morden]] in 1923, as well as incorporating the [[City and South London Railway]], which had been rebuilt with larger tunnels. 191 cars were ordered from three manufacturers in 1923, which were formed into five-car trains.{{sfn|Bruce |1988 |pp=53\u201354}} The City and South London Railway had been built with tunnels which were only {{convert|10.5|ft|m}} in diameter, and had used [[London Underground electric locomotives|small electric locomotives]] to haul trailer cars until it closed for rebuilding in 1923. The reconstruction was completed in 1925,{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |pp=7, 16}} and 69 of the new vehicles were owned by them, while the rest were owned by the London Electric Railway Company.{{sfn|Bruce |1988 |pp=53\u201354}}\n\nIn a departure from previous practice, where all traction control equipment had been supplied by [[British Thomson-Houston]] (BTH), most of the batch were fitted with equipment by Metropolitan-Vickers, which consisted of electro-magnetic contactors arranged to manage the acceleration of the train automatically, with switching from series to parallel connection of the motors handled by bridging them rather than open-circuiting them. Two motor cars had equipment by [[General Electric Company plc|General Electric Co]] (GEC), which worked similarly, and was required to work in multiple with the Metropolitan-Vickers equipment. All the vehicles used a C-type door operating engine, which proved to be a poor design. Another 127 cars were ordered in 1924, with most of the motor cars and some of the control trailers using GEC equipment. Cars with GEC controls used WT54 motors, which those with Metropolitan-Vickers equipment used MV152 motors, and although they were interchangeable in theory, in practice they were always kept in pairs. The 1924 cars were fitted with a D-type door engine, which was reclassified as a DL-type after a minor modification had to be made, but proved much more resilient than the earlier C-type, and was used on all Standard Stock until 1931.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |pp=54\u201356}}\n\nDelivery of the cars was not easy, as the Hampstead Line did not have a mainline railway connection to any other line. Consequently, the bodies and bogies were delivered by road, and two large gantries were erected at both Morden and Golders Green depots. A traction engine would arrive at the site with the body, and would position it below the gantries. It would then be raised so that the road wheels could be removed, and a steam crane would position the bogies onto the track. Once the body and bogies were united, a steam engine would remove the complete car, to allow the next one to be assembled.{{sfn|Bruce |1968 |pp=42\u201343}}\n\nA further 120 cars were ordered in 1925, with both types of equipment, to cope with the opening of the junction at Kennington and the lengthening of trains to six cars and from 1926, seven cars. Motor cars seated 30 passengers, while trailers had 48 seats. Control trailers had a cab at one end, but no switch compartment, and so seated four less. Trains initially had a crew of three, consisting of a motorman, a front conductor, and a rear guard. The guard signalled the conductor that the train was ready to go, and the conductor signalled the motorman. Once the use of air-operated doors had proved to be successful, modifications were made to enable a train to be operated by a crew of two. Changes included the fitting of a telephone, so that the guard and motorman could communicate, interlocks to ensure that all doors were closed, and the re-routing of the starting bell, so that it could be operated by a guard at the rear of the train, rather than the conductor at the front. These changes were completed by 1927, allowing the reduction of the train crew.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |pp=55\u201357}}\n\n=== 1926 and 1927 builds ===\nThe superior nature of the new trains helped to show up the inadequacies of plans to convert large numbers of gate stock cars to have air doors, and they were largely abandoned. Another 112 cars, all fitted with GEC equipment, were ordered from Metropolitan Carriage Wagon and Finance in 1926, and an order for 170 cars followed on in 1927. This enabled trains to be increased to seven cars, and more trains to be operated. A second order was placed with MCWF in 1927, for 136 more cars, but the traction control equipment was supplied by British Thomson-Houston. Their equipment generally proved to be more reliable, and previous batches of Standard Stock were modified so that the main contactors could be replaced with BTH equipment. BTH continued to be the preferred supplier for this equipment for the next 35 years. Metropolitan-Vickers supplied their own motors, but Standard Stock built by other manufacturers used GEC motors. The inter-operability of cars from several manufacturers with three types of traction control was the reason that they were called Standard Stock.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=59}}\n\nThe 1927 builds used a 'Z' bogie, instead of the previous 'Y' bogie, which had wheels of {{convert|36|in|cm}} diameter, as opposed to {{convert|40|in|cm}}. This required a modification to the WT54 motors, supplied by GEC, which were then known as WT54A motors, and the gearing was altered so that cars with either size of wheels remained compatible. Trials with the 'loudaphone' system by which the guard and motorman could communicate on this stock resulted in it being retro-fitted to the earlier stock.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |pp=59\u201361}}\n\nDuring this period, many of the Gate Stock cars on the Central line had been converted to air-door operation by the Union Construction Co., which was based at Feltham. Plans were briefly formulated to convert the Gate Stock on the Piccadilly and Bakerloo lines, but analysis showed that the cost of building a new car was only slightly more than the cost of converting an old one, and so an order for 182 new cars was placed. They were known as the 1927 Feltham Stock, although the door plates carried the date 1928, and they were not delivered until 1929 and 1930. The lightweight construction caused problems in later years, when the seat risers and body bolsters developed fractures. With the batch of cars built by MCWF and fitted with BTH equipment, these vehicles enabled Gate Stock to be withdrawn from the Piccadilly line in June 1929, and from the Bakerloo line on 1 January 1930.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=62}}\n\n=== 1929 and 1930 builds ===\nAnother 53 cars were ordered from the Union Construction Co. in 1929, to enable the remaining 1920 Stock cars, which had air doors but were not really suitable for operation on the open sections of the Piccadilly line, to be transferred to the Bakerloo line. An extra train of two motor cars and four trailers was ordered in 1930, to test several new features. They were the last cars to be built by the Union Construction Co., for it was closed as a result of political pressure in 1932. The new motor cars were {{convert|1|ft|m|2}} longer, and the trailers were {{convert|2|ft|m}} longer. This was achieved by tapering one or both ends, to prevent them fouling the [[structure gauge]] on curves. On two of the trailers, the centre door openings were widened from {{convert|4|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} to {{convert|5|ft|2|in|m|abbr=on}}. On the other two, the width of the centre doors was not altered, but the seating capacity was reduced from 48 to 40, to allow the provision of an additional single-leaf door at both ends of the car. The position of the guard's door control panel was altered, although this was not found to be satisfactory, and was dropped from subsequent builds.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |pp=63\u201364}}\n\nBecause of the Piccadilly extensions, which were above ground, heaters were fitted, and the use of British materials in its construction was used for publicity purposes, at a time when there was an industrial depression. It became known as the 'All British' train, and operated on the Piccadilly and Northern lines. Transfer between the two was aided by the construction of a junction at Kings Cross in 1927. The Northern line offered heavier traffic, with which to assess the effectiveness of the new features. 62 production cars were ordered from Metropolitan-Cammell, which was formed from the Metropolitan Carriage Wagon and Finance Co. and Cammell Laird at this time, for delivery to the Bakerloo line. They replaced the Watford Joint Stock, which although relatively new, needed a larger crew and had to stop for longer at stations, because of its swing doors. Problems with the swing doors were highlighted by a fatal accident in which a passenger got caught in them, but the door interlock did not detect it.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |pp=64\u201365}}\n\nThis build was not initially compatible with other builds, because it was fitted with an electro-pneumatic braking system, as well as the Westinghouse air brake. To accommodate its control, an extra 10-core control jumper was fitted, and previous builds of Standard Stock were gradually altered to include the extra wires, a process which was largely completed by 1936. Standard Stock motor cars which were running on the Bakerloo line with Cammell Laird 1920 Stock trailers were not fitted with the electro-pneumatic brake wiring until the trailers were withdrawn in 1938.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |pp=65\u201366}}\n\n=== 1931 and 1934 builds ===\nIn 1929, government aid enabled plans for extensions to the Piccadilly line northwards to Cockfosters and westwards from [[Hammersmith tube station (District and Piccadilly lines)|Hammersmith]] to Acton Town, on tracks which were parallel to the District line but not shared with it, to come to fruition. The length of the line increased from {{convert|8.5|mi|km}} to {{convert|40|mi|km}}, and so more trains were needed. The improvements made for the 1930 build were incorporated into the design, as well as some new features. 145 motor cars were ordered from Metropolitan-Cammell, and 130 trailer cars were shared between two builders. All trailer cars had 12 doors, with two sets of double doors and a single-leaf door at both ends on each side. Electro-pneumatic brakes were fitted, as was a weak-field control, which enabled higher speed running and had been tested on the 1930 build. Its use on the Northern line had demonstrated that the same service intervals could be maintained with four fewer trains.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |pp=67\u201369}}\n\nThe final build of Standard Stock was a small batch of 26 motor cars ordered from Metropolitan-Cammell in 1934, after the formation of the London Passenger Transport Board in the previous year. The Piccadilly line was extended from South Harrow to Uxbridge, and this required an extra eight seven-car trains. These were made up from the new motor cars and some reshuffling of stock between other lines. Although very similar to the 1931 build, there were some minor differences. The 1931 build had used motors with roller bearings for the first time, and ten of the new motor cars were also fitted with roller bearing axle boxes, to reduce the amount of maintenance required with white metal bearings.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=69}} With the completion of the 1934 build, the total number of Standard Stock cars was 645 motor cars, 551 trailers and 270 control trailers.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=127}}\n\n== Allocation ==\nBy the time the final cars had been delivered, the standard stock was operating on the Northern, Piccadilly and Bakerloo lines. There were 724 cars on the Northern line, consisting of 336 motor cars, 243 trailers and 145 control trailers. This group comprised all of the cars made in 1923, 1924, 1925 and 1926, supplemented by 62 per cent of the 1927 build by Metropolitan, and 13 of the 1927-built Feltham cars. The Piccadilly line had 509 cars, comprising some of the 1927 Metropolitan and Feltham batches, most of the 1929 Feltham stock, the experimental 1930 Feltham train, and all of the 1931 and 1934 stock. The Bakerloo line also had some of the 1927 Metropolitan and Feltham batches, four cars from the 1929 Feltham build and the 1930 Metropolitan stock. This was a total of 198 cars, made up of 82 motor cars, 62 trailers and 54 control trailers. To make up the number of trains, an additional 20 trailers and 20 control trailers were needed, and these were cars of 1920 Cammell Laird air-door stock.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=127}}\n\nBetween 1935 and 1940, the London Underground benefited from a New Works Programme worth \u00a340 million. This included extensions to the Northern line and the Central line, with delivery of new trains of [[London Underground 1938 Stock|1938 Stock]] beginning in May 1938. The intention was to run the new trains on the Northern line, and transfer the displaced Standard Stock to the Central line, which was using stock built in 1900\u20131903. In addition, some of the displaced stock would be used on the Moorgate-Finsbury Park \"Highbury Branch\", also known as the [[Northern City Line]], and some would be used to increase the length of trains on the Bakerloo line to seven cars. 82 control trailers were converted to trailers, and 21 driving motor cars were altered from \"A\" cars to \"D\" cars, as the makeup of 7 car trains on the Bakerloo and Central lines had the three-car unit at the opposite end to those on the Northern line.{{sfn |Hardy |1986 |pp=70-71}}\n\nThe Northern City Line had previously been served by surface stock, and had to be modified to accommodate the Standard Stock. Additionally, it had a non-standard arrangement of the third and fourth rails which supplied power to the cars, and these were modified to the same configuration as on the Northern line during the refurbishment.{{sfn |Hardy |1986 |p=71}} The use of control trailers at one end of a short train was virtually discontinued during the 1930s, because of the risks of disruption to services. A 3-car train consisted on a driving motor car, a trailer and a control trailer (DM-T-CT) and only had one compressor on the motor car. If it failed, the train was stranded, causing delays, whereas a 4-car short train had two motor cars (DM-T-T-DM) and hence two compressors. Failure of one did not prevent the train continuing.{{sfn|Hardy|2001|p=31}} The exception to the use of control trailers was the off-peak trains on the Northern City Line, which consisted of a driving motor car and a control trailer, and these 2-car trains continued to run until October 1964.{{sfn |Hardy |1981 |p=17}}\n\n===Central line===\nOn the [[Central line (London Underground)|Central line]], Standard Stock began replacing the [[London Underground 1900/1903 Stock|1900/1903 Stock]] in the autumn of 1938, and this action was completed by mid-1939. The Central line used a three-rail system, with a central conductor rail supplying the power, and was not converted to a four-rail system until May 1940. All of the trains were therefore converted to work with the three-rail system as an interim measure, and then converted back to four-rail operation once the track had been modified.{{sfn |Hardy |1986 |p=71}}\n\nAt the time, extensions to [[West Ruislip tube station|West Ruislip]], [[Epping tube station|Epping]] and [[Hainault tube station|Hainault]] were under construction, which would require more trains, but the onset of the [[Second World War]] resulted in the extensions being postponed. Nearly 200 cars were stored in the partially built Hainault depot, but that was then requisitioned by the U.S. Army Transportation Corps, and the cars were moved to open sidings. Others were stored on sidings at Edgware, Golders Green, Highgate, Morden, Neasden, and Stanmore, as well as in depots where there was spare capacity. Some of the motor cars were painted grey, and used for engineering duties. Some trains were used for \"Tube Refreshment Specials\", supplying food and drink to people sheltering from air raids on the underground platforms.{{sfn |Hardy |2001 |p=33}}\n\nAfter the war ended, the Central line extensions opened, reaching Stratford on 4 December 1946, Newbury Park and Woodford on 14 December 1947, West Ruislip, Loughton and Hainault on 21 November 1948, and Epping on 25 September 1949.{{sfn |Bruce |1968 |pp=75-76}} The effects of six or more years of open-air storage on the Standard Stock was severe, and a programme of heavy refurbishment began, which included replacement of warped window frames, renewal of corroded equipment as necessary, and in many cases, complete rewiring. Stations had been lengthened to accommodate 8-car trains before the war, but trains were restricted to 6 cars until the depot at White City could be altered. Some 7-car trains began operating from November 1947, and 8-car trains from the following January. However, the reliability of the refurbished cars was poor, and a full service of 8-car trains was not achieved{{sfn |Hardy |2001 |pp=36-37}} until additional cars became available from other lines, following the delivery of the [[London Underground 1959 Stock|1959 Stock]]. The achievement was short-lived, as all Standard Stock had been withdrawn from the Central line less than three years later.{{sfn |Bruce |1968 |pp=76-77}}\n\n8-car trains were formed of two 4-car units, each consisting of two driving motor cars and two trailers (DM-T-T-DM). This arrangement was not ideal at busy times, since there was a section in the middle of the train where there were no passenger doors for almost {{convert|50|ft|m}}, caused by the switch compartments behind the driving cabs. In order to alleviate the problem, one of the four-car units was split, and two cars were placed at either end of the other unit. The formation from 1961 thus became DM-T x DM-T-T-DM x T-DM, which reduced loading times at peak periods.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=72}}\n\n== Disposal ==\n1938 Stock replaced the Standard Stock on the Bakerloo line, the changeover being completed on 23 May 1949,{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=72}} although a batch of 1927-built trailers (usually referred to as \"58 trailers\" because of the number of cars in the group rather than a year reference, as was normally the case with Tube stock classes) were converted to operate with the new stock on the Bakerloo line.{{sfn |Hardy |1976 |p=76}} The Standard Stock on the Piccadilly line was eventually replaced by the [[London Underground 1959 Stock|1959 Stock]]. This enabled the first large-scale withdrawals and scrapping of Standard Stock, although some of the better cars were transferred to the Central line to complete the 8-car trains.{{sfn |Bruce |1968 |p=76}}\n\nLondon Transport intended to use the prototype [[London Underground 1960 Stock|1960 Stock]] to develop new trains to replace the Standard Stock on the Central line: however, the condition of the 30\u201340 year-old Central line fleet were deteriorating under an intense service pattern, exacerbated by growing demand from the expansion of electric trains in the [[Eastern Region of British Railways]].{{sfn |Hardy |1981 |p=25}} The situation escalated with a [[List of London Underground accidents#Holland Park and Redbridge fires|fatal electrical fire]] on car 3465 near Holland Park in 1958, and another (non-fatal) fire on car 3673 near Redbridge in 1960.{{sfn |Bruce |1988 |p=72}}\n\nIn response to the fires, London Transport diverted 57 of the 76 trains from the [[London Underground 1959 Stock|1959 Stock]] to debut on the Central line instead of the Piccadilly line, and ordered another 57 non-driving motor cars that would later form part of the near-identical [[London Underground 1962 Stock|1962 Stock]].{{sfn |Bruce |1968 |p=87}} London Transport also retained some Standard Stock cars from the Piccadilly line to replace the worst performing cars on the Central line.<ref name=\"Connor\">{{cite journal|last=Connor|first=Piers|title=The London Electric Train|journal=Underground News|date=January 2017|issue=668|page=540|publisher=London Underground Railway Society|issn=0306-8617}}</ref>\n\nLondon Transport withdrew the last Standard Stock trains from the Central line in June 1963. The arrival of the 1962 stock in the previous year then allowed the 1959 stock to complete the withdrawal of the Standard Stock from the Piccadilly line by July 1964, which in turn allowed the 1938 Stock to replace the last Standard Stock trains from the Northern City Line, on 3 November 1966.{{sfn|Hardy|1981|p=25}}<ref name=\"Connor\"/>\n\nA number of motor cars saw further service as [[London Underground departmental stock|departmental vehicles]]. 16 were used as ballast motor cars, with many of them lasting until 1978, and four were used as pilot motor cars.{{sfn |Bruce |1987 |pp=91-92}} Motor car 3327 was displayed in the Science Museum, London, for many years, but returned to the London Transport Museum in 1996.{{sfn |Hardy |2002 |p=60}}\n\n== Isle of Wight ==\n[[File:Ryde Pier Head Martin Addison.jpg|thumb|1927 Stock train arriving at [[Ryde Pier Head station.]]]]\nPrior to 1950, there were {{convert|55.5|mi|km}} of steam-operated railways on the [[Isle of Wight]]. This was reduced to {{convert|25.5|mi|km}} between 1952 and 1956, and to just {{convert|8.5|mi|km}} in 1966. The Ryde Pier Head\u2013Shanklin section (the [[Island Line, Isle of Wight|Island Line]]) was retained and electrified,{{sfn |Hardy |2003 |p=9}} but because of the restricted loading gauge at Ryde Tunnels, smaller-than-normal trains were required.{{sfn |Hardy |2003 |p=4}}\n\nThe [[Southern Region of British Railways|Southern Region]] approached London Transport in 1961, to begin negotiations for some of the Standard Stock then being withdrawn. The initial plan was to fit diesel engines into the motor cars, and to use either electric or mechanical transmission.{{sfn |Hardy |2003 |pp=10\u201311}} The first twelve cars were transferred from [[Ruislip]] Depot to [[Wimbledon station|Wimbledon]] in August 1964, from where they were moved to [[Micheldever]] sidings. Further cars followed in June 1965.{{sfn |Hardy |2003 |pp=12\u201313}} In October, a plan to electrify the line was announced, and the idea of fitting diesel engines was dropped. In 1966, the Southern Region had 44 cars at Micheldever, and London Transport had 29 more which were set aside for the scheme. 10 of the Micheldever cars were scrapped, and 12 more were obtained from London Transport.{{sfn |Hardy |2003 |pp=14\u201315}}\n\nOverhaul of the electrical and braking systems was done at Acton Works, which involved transferring the cars from Micheldever back to London Transport. This included conversion to work with a [[Third rail|three-rail]] system, rather than the standard London Transport [[Railway electrification system#Fourth rail|four-rail]] system. The number of cars to be shipped to the Isle of Wight was reduced from 46 to 43 because of the cost of this work. After overhaul, the cars were transferred to [[Stewarts Lane]], where they were repainted in British Rail blue, and were then taken to the Isle of Wight.{{sfn |Hardy |2003 |pp=16\u201317}} They were loaded onto a road vehicle at [[Fratton railway station|Fratton]] belonging to the haulage company [[Pickfords]], and crossed to the island on the [[Wightlink|Portsmouth to Fishbourne ferry]]. Care was needed to ensure that the weather and tides were suitable, and motor cars had to be transferred on special sailings, rather than regular crossings, because of the difficulty of unloading a vehicle of this weight without damaging the ship's unloading ramp.{{sfn |Hardy |2003 |p=18}}\n\nThe cars were formed into 4-car and 3-car units, initially designated as 4-VEC and 3-TIS units.{{sfn |Hardy |2003 |p=18}} Subsequently, they became Classes 452 and 451, and were later reclassified to become [[British Rail Classes 485 and 486|Classes 485 and 486]]. Apart from those cut up following accidents at [[Ryde depot]], and other early withdrawals, most of these units were withdrawn between 1988 and 1991,{{sfn |Hardy |2003 |p=90}} when they were replaced by [[London Underground 1938 Stock]]. In October 1990, five cars were returned to London Transport, to form a Heritage Train. They worked under their own power between Fratton and Wimbledon, and were displayed at an open day at Morden Depot, celebrating 100 years of the Northern line.{{sfn |Hardy |2003 |pp=48\u201352}}\n\n== Manufacturers ==\nStandard Stock is used to describe six experimental cars built by five manufacturers in 1923, and 18 batches of production cars, totalling 1460 vehicles, built by six manufacturers between 1923 and 1934.<ref>{{harvnb |Bruce |1988 |p=127}} (table data included)</ref> It became the most prolific class of stock to run on the Underground,{{sfn |Hardy |1986 |p=4}} which was partly due to the [[Trade Facilities Act 1921]]. This was a government initiative in the aftermath of the [[First World War]] to fund schemes which would create employment, particularly in the construction, steel and manufacturing industries. The Underground benefited from \u00a35 million of investment from this source, which in addition to funding extensions to the Northern line, financed the construction of over 1,100 Standard Stock cars between 1922 and 1930.{{sfn |Halliday |2013 |pp=101-105}}\n{|\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Builder\n!Motors\n!Trailers\n!Control<br>Trailers\n!Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=8; align=center |1923\n|align=center|BRCW\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|\u2014\n|rowspan=5|Experimental<br>stock\n|-\n|align=center|CLCo\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|align=center|GRCW\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|1\n|-\n|align=center|Leeds\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|align=center|MCWF\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|align=center|BRCW\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|35\n|align=center|-\n|rowspan=18|Production<br />stock\n|-\n|align=center|CLCo\n|align=center|41\n|align=center|40\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|align=center|MCWF\n|align=center|40\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|35\n|-\n|rowspan=3; align=center |1924\n|align=center|BRCW\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|50\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|align=center|CLCo\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|25\n|-\n|align=center|MCWF\n|align=center|52\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|rowspan=2; align=center |1925\n|align=center|CLCo\n|align=center|48\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|align=center|MCWF\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|67\n|-\n|align=center |1926\n|align=center|MCWF\n|align=center|64\n|align=center|48\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|rowspan=2; align=center |1927\n|align=center|MCWF\n|align=center|110\n|align=center|160\n|align=center|36\n|-\n|align=center|UCC\n|align=center|77\n|align=center|37\n|align=center|68\n|-\n|align=center |1929\n|align=center|UCC\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|17\n|align=center|18\n|-\n|rowspan=2; align=center|1930\n|align=center|MCCW\n|align=center|22\n|align=center|20\n|align=center|20\n|-\n|align=center|UCC\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|rowspan=3; align=center|1931\n|align=center|BRCW\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|90\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|align=center|GRCW\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|40\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|align=center|MCCW\n|align=center|145\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|align=center|1934\n|align=center|MCCW\n|align=center|26\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n!Totals\n|align=center|1,466\n|align=center|645\n|align=center|551\n|align=center|270\n| &nbsp;\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Key to Builders\n|-\n|BRCW\n|[[Birmingham Railway Carriage and Wagon Company|Birmingham Railway Carriage & Wagon Co.]]\n|-\n|CLCo\n|[[Cammell Laird|Cammell Laird & Co. Ltd.]]\n|-\n|GRCW\n|[[Gloucester Railway Carriage and Wagon Company|Gloucester Railway Carriage & Wagon Co.]]\n|-\n|Leeds\n|[[Leeds Forge Company]]\n|-\n|MCCW\n|[[Metro Cammell|Metropolitan-Cammell Carriage & Wagon Company Ltd.]]\n|-\n|MCWF\n|[[Metro Cammell|Metropolitan Carriage, Wagon & Finance Co.]]\n|-\n|UCC\n|[[Union Construction Company]] (\"Feltham\")\n|}\n|}\n\n== Preservation ==\nSeveral vehicles have been preserved:{{sfn |Hardy |2002 |p=112}} <!-- page no needs checking&nbsp;\u2014 might be total pages. I think this is a later edition of Hardy -->\n{|\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Number<ref group=T>First number is last number assigned when in passenger service; second number is IoW fleet number (2\u201349) or LT service stock number (L13x locomotives or PC85x personnel carriers).</ref>\n!Type\n!Built\n!Builder\n!Location\n|-align=center\n|3327\n|\u2014\n|DM\n|1927\n|MCCW\n|align=left|[[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum, Acton Depot]]\n|-align=center\n|3370\n|L134\n|DM\n|1927\n|MCCW\n|align=left|[[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum, Acton Depot]]\n|-align=center\n|3693\n|L131\n|DM\n|1927\n|MCCW\n|align=left|[[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum, Acton Depot]]\n|-align=center\n|5279\n|27\n|CT\n|1925\n|MCCW\n|align=left|[[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum, Acton Depot]]\n|-align=center\n|7296\n|49\n|T\n|1923\n|CLCo\n|align=left|[[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum, Acton Depot]]\n|}\n|colspan=15 valign=\"top\"|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Key to Type\n|-\n!align=center|CT\n|nowrap|Control Trailer\n|-\n!align=center|DM\n|Driving Motor\n|-\n!align=center|T\n|Trailer\n|}\n|}\n{{Reflist|group=T}}\nFour cars owned by the London Transport Museum have been formed into a four-car unit, consisting of DM 3370, DM 3693, CT 5279 and T 7296 at their Acton Depot. They are awaiting restoration.\n\nSeveral cars that were preserved have since been scrapped.\n* DM 3209 / 7 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4795 |title=3209 Standard Stock Driving Motor |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* DM 3690 / L130 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4730 |title=London Electric 3690 Standard stock driving motor |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* DM 3701 / L135 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4731 |title=London Electric 3701 Standard stock driving motor |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* DM 3706 / 2 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4797 |title=3706 Standard Stock Driving Motor |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* T 7061 / PC850 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4732 |title=London Electric 7061 Trailer car |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* T 7063 / PC851 scrapped at Acton Works 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4733 |title=London Electric 7063 Trailer car |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* T 7071 / PC855 scrapped at Acton Works 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=4734 |title=London Electric 7071 Trailer car |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n* T 7281 / 44 scrapped at Acton Works 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3283 |title=Underground Electric Railways 7281 1923 Tube Stock |publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n  |first=J Graeme|last=Bruce\n  |title=Tube Trains Under London\n  |publisher=London Transport Board\n  |year=1968\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n  |first=J Graeme|last=Bruce\n  |title=Workhorses of the London Underground\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=1987\n  |isbn=0-904711-87-0\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n  |first=J Graeme|last=Bruce\n  |title=The London Underground Tube Stock\n  |publisher=Ian Allan and London Transport Museum\n  |location=Shepperton\n  |year=1988\n  |isbn=978-0-7110-1707-8\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Stephen |last=Halliday\n  |title=Underground to Everywhere\n  |publisher=The History Press\n  |year=2013\n  |location=Stroud\n  |isbn=978-0-7524-9772-3\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=London Underground Rolling Stock\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=1976\n  |edition=1st\n  |location=London\n  |isbn=978-0-904711-01-1\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=L.P.T.B Rolling Stock 1933-1948\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |publisher=D Bradford Barton\n  |year=1981\n  |isbn=978-0-85153-436-7\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=Standard Tube Stock Part 1: 1922-1945\n  |publisher=London Underground Railway Society\n  |work=Underground\n  |issue=14\n  |year=1986\n  |issn=0306-8609\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last= Hardy\n  |title=Underground Train File: Tube Stock 1933-1959\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=2001\n  |location=London\n  |isbn=978-1-85414-235-1\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=London Underground Rolling Stock\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=2002\n  |edition=15th\n  |location=London\n  |isbn=978-1-85414-263-4\n  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=Tube Trains on the Isle of Wight\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=2003\n  |location=London\n  |isbn=978-1-85414-276-4\n  |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |year=1983\n  |title=\"Standard\" Tube Stock (A Photographic History) Part 1: 1922\u20131945\n  |periodical=Underground\n  |location=Hemel Hempstead, Hertfordshire\n  |publisher=London Underground Railway Society\n  |issue=14\n  |issn=0306-8609\n  }}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=\"Standard\" Tube Stock (A Photographic History) Part 2 \u2013 1945 Onwards\n  |publisher=London Underground Railway Society\n  |year=1987\n  |location = Hemel Hempstead, Hertfordshire\n  |isbn=978-1-870324-15-1\n  }}\n* {{Cite book\n  |first=Brian |last=Hardy\n  |title=Underground Train File: Tube Stock 1933-1959\n  |publisher=Capital Transport\n  |year=2001\n  |location=London\n  |isbn=978-1-85414-235-1\n  }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/collections/collections-online/photographs London Transport Museum Photographic Archive]\n** {{ltmcollection|g2/i0000eg2.jpg|Standard Stock trains at Morden Depot, 1938}}\n** {{ltmcollection|ob/i00005ob.jpg|Standard Stock train at Hammersmith, 1935}}\n** {{ltmcollection|mm/i00009mm.jpg|Standard Stock trailer car at Waterloo, 1936}}\n** {{ltmcollection|ms/i0000ams.jpg|Interior view of Standard Stock car, 1935}}\n\n{{London Underground Rolling Stock}}\n{{Bakerloo line navbox}}\n{{Central line navbox}}\n{{Northern line navbox}}\n{{Piccadilly line navbox}}\n\n[[Category:London Underground electric multiple units|1923]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan Cammell multiple units]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 1923]]\n", "name_user": "C2A", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction stock:changing 'four less' to 44 to avoid confusion with 26.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London_Underground_Standard_Stock"}
{"title_page": "Jabal Haraz", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = Jabal Haraz\n| native_name       = {{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632}}\n| native_name_lang  = ar\n| photo             = Yemen (11462772954).jpg\n| photo_caption     = A building with terraces overlooks the side of one of the Haraz mountains\n| country           = {{YEM}}\n| region_type       = \n| region            = Asia\n| border            =\n| highest           = \n| elevation_m       = 3,000\n| highest_location  = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|15.1667|N|43.7500|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n| range_coordinates =\n| length_km         = \n| geology           =\n| period            =\n| orogeny           =\n| map               = Yemen#Middle East#Asia\n| map_image         = \n| map_caption       = \n}}\n\n'''Jabal Haraz''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632|Jabal \u1e24ar\u0101z}}) is a mountainous region of [[Yemen]], between [[Sanaa]] and [[Al Hudaydah|Al-Hudaydah]], which is considered to be within the [[Sarawat Mountains|Sarat range]].<ref name=\"CookFarmer2013\">{{cite book |last1=Cook |first1=John |last2=Farmer |first2=G. Thomas |title=Climate Change Science: A Modern Synthesis |volume=1 \u2013 The Physical Climate |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer Science & Business Media]] |chapter=VI: Land and Its Climates |page=334 |isbn=9-4007-5757-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tbtEAAAAQBAJ&dq=sarawat+mountains&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2013-01-12}}</ref> In the 11th century, it was the stronghold of the [[Sulaihid State|Sulaihid]] dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive today.<ref name=unesco>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1722/ |title=Jabal Haraz |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |date=2002-07-08 |access-date=2009-03-24}}</ref> They include [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]], the highest mountain in Yemen and the [[Arabian Peninsula]].<ref name=\"Laughlin2008\">{{cite book |last=McLaughlin |first=Daniel |title=Yemen |publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]] |chapter=1: Background |page=3 |isbn=978-1-8416-2212-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQvhZaEVzjcC&pg |year=2008}}</ref>\n\n== History and location ==\nBecause of its location between the [[Tihamah]] coastal plain and Sanaa, this mountainous area has always been strategically important. A caravan stopping point during the [[Himyarite Kingdom]], the Haraz was later the stronghold of the [[Sulayhid dynasty]], which was established in Yemen in 1037. Then and subsequently the population have been [[Ism'aili]] [[Shia Islam|Shi'ite]] [[Muslim]]s.\n\nHaraz is as famous for its fortified villages which cling to nearly inaccessible rocky peaks. Their imposing architecture meets two needs: defending the villagers, while leaving plenty of space for crops. Each town is built like a castle; the houses, themselves, form the wall, equipped with one or two easily defensible doors. Constructed from sandstone and basalt, the buildings are integrated into the landscape and it is difficult to tell where the rock and the village begins or ends. The mountain is divided into terraces of a few acres or more, separated by walls sometimes several meters high. On these terraced fields grow alfalfa for livestock, millet, lentils, large areas for coffee and [[Khat|qat]].\n\nWithin a day's journey are [[Bani Murrah]] and other villages located on the ridge overlooking [[Manakhah]]. Manakhah is the heart of mountain range, a large town whose market attracts villagers from the entire neighbourhood. [[Al Hajjara]], to the west of Manakhah, is a walled village whose citadel was founded in the 12th century by the Sulayhids. From there, other villages are accessible, such as [[Bayt al-Qamus]]  and [[Bayt Shimran]]. The village of [[Hutaib]] is built on a platform of red sandstone, facing a view of terraced hills which host a score of villages. Here also is the mausoleum of the third Yemeni ''[[Da'i al-Mutlaq]]'' [[Hatim ibn Ibrahim]]. [[Mustaali|Bohras]] from [[India]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Madagascar]] and other countries gather here.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n== World Heritage Status ==\nThis area was added to the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage]] Tentative List on July 8, 2002, in the mixed (cultural and natural) category, as a site that has \"outstanding universal value\".<ref name=unesco/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Haraz 200612 Yemen-115 (353667843).jpg|A terraced mountain side in [[Al Mahwit Governorate]] near [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]] (the highest mountain in the [[Arabian Peninsula]])\nFile:\u0645\u0646\u062a\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062f\u0633\u064a\u0629 - panoramio.jpg|Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb is behind the mountain in the background, facing west of southern [[Sanaa]]\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (12633745063).jpg|Jabal Haraz terraces\nFile:Manakha 01.jpg|[[Manakhah]]\nFile:Haraz Mtns, Yemen (13970993973).jpg|Buildings at the base of a mountain\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (14616928081).jpg|Fortified settlement amid the mountains\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ad Dahrah]], located in the Haraz, the stronghold of the Sulaihid dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive to this day\n* [[Geology of Yemen]]\n* [[Hajhir Mountains]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120922020555/http://www.lonelyplanet.com/yemen/the-harazmountains Lonely Planet]\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Jabal Haraz}}\n* [https://www.architecturerevived.com/architectural-beauty-out-of-poverty-jabal-haraz-yemen/ Architecture Revived: Architectural Beauty out of Poverty, Jabal Haraz Yemen]\n* [http://medomed.org/featured_item/jabal-bura-and-jabal-haraz-the-mountanous-cultural-landscape-of-yemen-yemen/ Med-O-Med: Cultural landscapes: Jabal Bura and Jabal Haraz, Yemen]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DcgXBQlPUJs Jabal Haraz] ([[YouTube]])\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qqJSqAjtbCA Yemen - Haraz Mountains]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mbooIXhPq-E Yemen 2008 Jebel Haraz]\n\n{{Tourist attractions in Yemen}}\n{{Mountains in the Arabian Peninsula}}\n\n[[Category:Jabal Haraz|*]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of mainland Yemen]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = Jabal Haraz\n| native_name       = {{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632}}\n| native_name_lang  = ar\n| photo             = Yemen (11462772954).jpg\n| photo_caption     = A building with terraces overlooks the side of one of the Haraz mountains\n| country           = {{YEM}}\n| region_type       = \n| region            = Asia\n| border            =\n| highest           = \n| elevation_m       = 3,000\n| highest_location  = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|15.1667|N|43.7500|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n| range_coordinates =\n| length_km         = \n| geology           =\n| period            =\n| orogeny           =\n| map               = Yemen#Middle East#Asia\n| map_image         = \n| map_caption       = \n}}\n\n'''Jabal Haraz''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632|Jabal \u1e24ar\u0101z}}) is a mountainous region of [[Yemen]], between [[Sanaa]] and [[Al Hudaydah|Al-Hudaydah]], which is considered to be within of the [[Sarawat Mountains|Sarat range]].<ref name=\"CookFarmer2013\">{{cite book |last1=Cook |first1=John |last2=Farmer |first2=G. Thomas |title=Climate Change Science: A Modern Synthesis |volume=1 \u2013 The Physical Climate |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer Science & Business Media]] |chapter=VI: Land and Its Climates |page=334 |isbn=9-4007-5757-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tbtEAAAAQBAJ&dq=sarawat+mountains&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2013-01-12}}</ref> In the 11th century, it was the stronghold of the [[Sulaihid State|Sulaihid]] dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive today.<ref name=unesco>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1722/ |title=Jabal Haraz |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |date=2002-07-08 |access-date=2009-03-24}}</ref> They include [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]], the highest mountain in Yemen and the [[Arabian Peninsula]].<ref name=\"Laughlin2008\">{{cite book |last=McLaughlin |first=Daniel |title=Yemen |publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]] |chapter=1: Background |page=3 |isbn=978-1-8416-2212-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQvhZaEVzjcC&pg |year=2008}}</ref>\n\n== History and location ==\nBecause of its location between the [[Tihamah]] coastal plain and Sanaa, this mountainous area has always been strategically important. A caravan stopping point during the [[Himyarite Kingdom]], the Haraz was later the stronghold of the [[Sulayhid dynasty]], which was established in Yemen in 1037. Then and subsequently the population have been [[Ism'aili]] [[Shia Islam|Shi'ite]] [[Muslim]]s.\n\nHaraz is as famous for its fortified villages which cling to nearly inaccessible rocky peaks. Their imposing architecture meets two needs: defending the villagers, while leaving plenty of space for crops. Each town is built like a castle; the houses, themselves, form the wall, equipped with one or two easily defensible doors. Constructed from sandstone and basalt, the buildings are integrated into the landscape and it is difficult to tell where the rock and the village begins or ends. The mountain is divided into terraces of a few acres or more, separated by walls sometimes several meters high. On these terraced fields grow alfalfa for livestock, millet, lentils, large areas for coffee and [[Khat|qat]].\n\nWithin a day's journey are [[Bani Murrah]] and other villages located on the ridge overlooking [[Manakhah]]. Manakhah is the heart of mountain range, a large town whose market attracts villagers from the entire neighbourhood. [[Al Hajjara]], to the west of Manakhah, is a walled village whose citadel was founded in the 12th century by the Sulayhids. From there, other villages are accessible, such as [[Bayt al-Qamus]]  and [[Bayt Shimran]]. The village of [[Hutaib]] is built on a platform of red sandstone, facing a view of terraced hills which host a score of villages. Here also is the mausoleum of the third Yemeni ''[[Da'i al-Mutlaq]]'' [[Hatim ibn Ibrahim]]. [[Mustaali|Bohras]] from [[India]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Madagascar]] and other countries gather here.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n== World Heritage Status ==\nThis area was added to the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage]] Tentative List on July 8, 2002, in the mixed (cultural and natural) category, as a site that has \"outstanding universal value\".<ref name=unesco/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Haraz 200612 Yemen-115 (353667843).jpg|A terraced mountain side in [[Al Mahwit Governorate]] near [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]] (the highest mountain in the [[Arabian Peninsula]])\nFile:\u0645\u0646\u062a\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062f\u0633\u064a\u0629 - panoramio.jpg|Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb is behind the mountain in the background, facing west of southern [[Sanaa]]\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (12633745063).jpg|Jabal Haraz terraces\nFile:Manakha 01.jpg|[[Manakhah]]\nFile:Haraz Mtns, Yemen (13970993973).jpg|Buildings at the base of a mountain\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (14616928081).jpg|Fortified settlement amid the mountains\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ad Dahrah]], located in the Haraz, the stronghold of the Sulaihid dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive to this day\n* [[Geology of Yemen]]\n* [[Hajhir Mountains]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120922020555/http://www.lonelyplanet.com/yemen/the-harazmountains Lonely Planet]\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Jabal Haraz}}\n* [https://www.architecturerevived.com/architectural-beauty-out-of-poverty-jabal-haraz-yemen/ Architecture Revived: Architectural Beauty out of Poverty, Jabal Haraz Yemen]\n* [http://medomed.org/featured_item/jabal-bura-and-jabal-haraz-the-mountanous-cultural-landscape-of-yemen-yemen/ Med-O-Med: Cultural landscapes: Jabal Bura and Jabal Haraz, Yemen]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DcgXBQlPUJs Jabal Haraz] ([[YouTube]])\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qqJSqAjtbCA Yemen - Haraz Mountains]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mbooIXhPq-E Yemen 2008 Jebel Haraz]\n\n{{Tourist attractions in Yemen}}\n{{Mountains in the Arabian Peninsula}}\n\n[[Category:Jabal Haraz|*]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of mainland Yemen]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List]]\n", "name_user": "Leo1pard", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jabal_Haraz"}
{"title_page": "Shannon Dallas", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian sit skier|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Shannon Dallas\n| image =File:090310 - Shannon Dallas at Vancouver 2010 Paralympics - 3b.jpg \n| caption =Shannon Dallas prior to the Vancouver 2010 Paralympic Games.\n| nationality = {{AUS}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1977|8|16}}\n| birth_place =  \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height =\n| weight =\n| country = Australia\n| sport = [[Para-alpine skiing]]\n| event = Downhill<br/>Super-G<br/>Giant slalom<br/>Slalom<br/>Super combined\n| collegeteam =\n| club = \n| worlds = \n| regionals = \n| nationals = \n| olympics = \n| paralympics = [[2010 Winter Paralympics]]\n| highestranking = \n| pb = \n| medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | [[Alpine skiing]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2009  High 1 Resort, Korea|Super G Sitting}}\n| imagesize =\n| fullname = \n| nicknames = \n}}\n'''Shannon Dallas''' (born 16 August 1977) is an Australian sit skier who receives support from the [[New South Wales Institute of Sport]]. Dallas participated in the [[2006 Winter Paralympics]] in [[Turin]], Italy, and the [[2010 Winter Paralympics]] in Vancouver, Canada.\n\n==Personal==\nBorn on 16 August 1977,<ref name=\"vancouver2010.paralympic.org.au\">{{cite web|url=http://vancouver2010.paralympic.org.au/team/shannon-dallas|title=Shannon Dallas|publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee|location=Australia|year=2010|accessdate=22 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815010941/http://vancouver2010.paralympic.org.au/team/shannon-dallas|archivedate=15 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dallas was a carpenter prior to an accident in 2000 where he broke his back<ref name=newspaper2/> after falling through a roof.<ref name=newspaper9>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Accident-free workers learn to keep it safe|newspaper=St Marys-Mt Druitt Star|location=Australia|date=29 November 2010|first=Kylie|last=Stevens|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:SMS8&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=137B3F729197EFD0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> He also used to be a surfie.<ref name=newspaper2/> When he was young, he moved around a lot.<ref name=newspaper4/> After finishing his [[Higher School Certificate (New South Wales)|HSC]], he moved to [[Toongabbie]] where he lived with a friend in a loungeroom.<ref name=newspaper4/> Dallas is from [[Terrigal]],<ref name=newspaper3>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Out of contention|newspaper=Central Coast Express Advocate|location=Sydney, Australia|date=24 March 2010|page=79|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12EA30831F947CE8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> New South Wales.<ref name=newspaper2/> He moved there in around 2003.<ref name=newspaper4/>\n\nDallas does work as a public speaker.<ref name=newspaper9/><ref name=crasssshhh/><ref name=motifivationalspeaker>{{cite news|url=http://www.bild.de/sport/mehr-sport/dallas/paralympic-star-will-lieber-liebe-statt-schnee-11892636.bild.html |title=Shannon Dallas: Paralympic-Athlet will lieber Liebe statt Schnee \u2013 Sport |location=Germany |language=de |publisher=Bild.de |date= |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> In 2010, he spoke at the [[Concord Library]] about his experiences with disability sport.<ref name=newspaper5/> That same year, he also spoke at [[Lend Lease Communities|Delfin Lend Lease]] about workplace safety.<ref name=newspaper9/>\n\nIn 2009 and 2010, Dallas worked in [[wheelchair basketball]] development on New South Wales's central coast. He also worked as a newspaper columnist.<ref name=crasssshhh/> In 2010, he played wheelchair basketball for the Sydney University Wheelkings.<ref name=crasssshhh/> He had four relationships in four years in the lead up to the 2010 Winter Paralympics. The demands of high level skiing was a factor in the relationships not working.<ref name=motifivationalspeaker/> In 2009, he had a shoulder reconstruction,<ref name=newspaper11/><ref name=newspaper1/> and other rehabilitation at the Mount Wilga Rehabilitation Hospital.<ref name=crasssshhh/> He also dealt with [[necrotising fasciitis]], a flesh-eating bug, that sidelined him for seven months.<ref name=newspaper2>{{Cite news|title=A battle against bugs and breaks|newspaper=The Courier Mail|location=Brisbane, Australia|date=18 March 2010|accessdate=22 October 2012|first=Amanda|last=Lulham|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACMB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E833A566DCB330&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9|page=79}}</ref><ref name=newspaper1/> The flesh-eating bug treatment involved a [[Skin grafting|skin graft]].<ref name=newspaper2/>\n\nDallas was featured on the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]'s ''X Paralympic Games'' in March 2010.<ref name=newspaper12>{{cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Critic's view Saturday, March 20|newspaper=The Age|location=Melbourne, Australia|date=18 March 2010|first=Conrad|last=Walters|page=32|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ASAB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E83CA4D9D812D8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref>\n\n==Skiing==\nDallas is a [[Monoski|sit-skier]].<ref name=motifivationalspeaker/><ref name=newspaper1/> When skiing, he can go {{convert|100|km}} an hour.<ref name=newspaper2/> He receives support from the [[New South Wales Institute of Sport]],<ref name=crasssshhh/><ref name=katelellis>{{cite web|url=http://www.health.gov.au/internet/ministers/publishing.nsf/Content/6B9704860CA28FAACA2576E3001850C2/$File/ke014.pdf|accessdate=24 October 2012|location=Australia|date=11 March 2010|first=Kate|last=Ellis|title=Winter Paralympians to inspire a nation|page=3|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229155208/http://www.health.gov.au/internet/ministers/publishing.nsf/Content/6B9704860CA28FAACA2576E3001850C2/$File/ke014.pdf|archivedate=29 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the [[Australian Institute of Sport]] and the Australian Government Sports Training Grants program.<ref name=katelellis>{{cite web|url=http://www.health.gov.au/internet/ministers/publishing.nsf/Content/6B9704860CA28FAACA2576E3001850C2/$File/ke014.pdf|accessdate=24 October 2012|location=Australia|date=11 March 2010|first=Kate|last=Ellis|title=Winter Paralympians to inspire a nation|page=3|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229155208/http://www.health.gov.au/internet/ministers/publishing.nsf/Content/6B9704860CA28FAACA2576E3001850C2/$File/ke014.pdf|archivedate=29 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2003, he competed at the [[Hartford Ski Spectacular]].<ref name=skiedthere>{{cite news |author=Ryan Slabaugh |url=http://www.vaildaily.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20031212/SPORTS/312120201 |title=Ryan Slabaugh |publisher=Vail Daily |date=12 December 2003 |location=Vail, Colorao |accessdate=22 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050120032543/http://www.vaildaily.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20031212%2FSPORTS%2F312120201 |archivedate=20 January 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> During the 2005/2006 World Cup skiing season, he had a second and third place finish in the giant slalom events.<ref name=withdrew/>\n[[File:210310 - Shannon Dallas slalom Vancouver Paralympics - 3b - crop.jpg|left|thumb|Shannon Dallas competing in the Slalom event at the Vancouver 2010 Paralympic Games.]]\nDallas competed at the [[2006 Winter Paralympics]],<ref name=newspaper4>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=ROOM FOR THOUGHT|newspaper=Central Coast Express Advocate |location=Sydney, Australia|date=7 May 2010|first=Nicole|last=Taylor|page=3|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1307E0F6F41D6A58&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> where he was the team captain. Coming into the Games, he was ranked in the top five in the world in the downhill and super-G.<ref name=withdrew/> While in Turin, his grandmother died.<ref name=newspaper11/> He finished ninth in the super-G and crashed in the downhill. Following his first run in the giant slalom, he was 34th with a time of 1:07.90. He climbed back to finish 18th overall in the giant slalom following his second run which had a time of 57.32 seconds. He withdrew from the Games before the slalom event, his last scheduled one.<ref name=withdrew>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/sport/skipper-quits-while-hes-ahead/2006/03/18/1142582578883.html |title=Skipper quits while he's ahead |publisher=The Age |location=Australia |date=18 March 2006 |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Dallas won a World Cup.<ref name=newspaper5>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Quicknews|newspaper=Inner West Courier&nbsp;\u2013 Inner West Edition|location=Sydney, Australia|date=22 June 2010 |page=3|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=137B3F729197EFD0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> In 2009, he won the World Championships for the super-G.<ref name=newspaper2/> He had a high speed crash at the 2009 IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships in Korea in the downhill event, which resulted in severe injuries that doctors thought might end his career.<ref name=newspaper2/><ref name=crasssshhh>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/team_info.cgi?client=0-4219-72986-0-8843498&sID=129341&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=8863337&sectionID=129341 |title=Gaetano, Shannon and Liesl updates |publisher=Sydney Uni WheelKings |date=17 April 2009 |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=horrowshow>{{cite web|first=Emma |last=Herd |url=http://express-advocate-wyong.whereilive.com.au/sport/story/dallas-makes-games-team-after-tough-year/ |title=Dallas makes Games team after tough year |publisher=Express Advocate Wyong Edition |location=Wyong, New South Wales |date= |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nDallas was officially named to the Australian 2010 Winter Paralympics team in November 2009.<ref name=officiallynamed>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/paralympic-team-for-vancover-sprinkled-with-experience/story-e6frg7mf-1225803724024 |title=Paralympic Team for Vancouver sprinkled with exaperience |publisher=The Australian |location=Australia |year=2009 |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref> A ceremony was held in Canberra with Australian Paralympic Committee president [[Greg Hartung]] and Minister for Sport [[Kate Ellis]] making the announcement.<ref name=makeannouncemnetellis>{{cite web|last=Browning |first=Jennifer |url=http://www.abc.net.au/sport/stories/2009/11/25/2753734.htm |title=Winter Paralympics team biggest yet |publisher=ABC Grandstand Sport |date=25 November 2009 |accessdate=24 October 2012 |location=Australia}}</ref> He and the rest of Australia's para-alpine team arrived in the Paralympic village on 9 March 2010.<ref name=arrivedvillage>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/australian-assault-on-paralympics-takes-shape-in-vancouver/story-fn4vwn8v-1225838309977 |title=Australian assault on Paralympics takes shape in Vancouver |first=Margie |last=McDonald |location=Australia |newspaper=The Australian |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref> At the Games, he competed in the super-G event, when he was the super-G world champion at the time.<ref name=newspaper1>{{Cite news|title=Aussie medal hopes left in tatters|newspaper=Sunday Telegraph |location=Sydney, Australia|date=21 March 2010|first=Amanda|last=Lulham|page=103|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ATLB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E833A566DCB330&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> In the super-G, he finished 12th.<ref name=newspaper1/> He also competed in the super combined,<ref name=newspaper1/> downhill and giant slalom events.<ref name=newspaper2/> He did not place in the super combined event as he failed to finish his second run<ref name=newspaper3/> because he crashed.<ref name=\"newspaper7\">{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Cam in double medal miracle|newspaper=Daily Telegraph |location=Sydney, Australia|date=22 March 2010|first=Amanda|last=Lulham|page=54|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ATLB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E98D657B94F9B8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref><ref name=\"newspaper7a\">{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Gold double for skier|newspaper=Hobart Mercury|location=Australia|date=22 March 2010|first=Amanda|last=Lulham|page=44|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:AHMB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E9A7A95DEA14C0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref><ref name=newspaper8>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=AAP News: PARA: Rahles-Rahbula claims \"miracle\" second bronze|agency=AAP News |location=Australia|date=21 March 2010|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:WAAP&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E96A02D8DFE798&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> He had been sitting in the sixth spot after his first run and kept sixth spot after his second run.<ref name=newspaper11>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Cold, wet weather a downer for Dallas|newspaper=Central Coast Express Advocate |location=Sydney, Australia|date=19 March 2010|first=Emma|last=Herd|page=77|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E88F0FD0F0DA60&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> He finished 11th in the super-G.<ref name=newspaper6>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=WEEKEND SCOREBOARD|newspaper=The Australian|location=Australia|date=22 March 2010|page=40|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:AUSB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E98D5A34AEDCB8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> He finished ninth in the super combined.<ref name=newspaper6/> He did not finish in the slalom.<ref name=newspaper6/> He overskied the giant slalom and finished sixth.<ref name=overskied>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-03-17/aussie-dallas-sixth-in-giant-slalom/368260 |title=Aussie Dallas sixth in giant slalom |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=17 March 2010 |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> The giant slalom course was difficult, and Dallas was one of only 30 out of 54 skiers to finish the course.<ref name=moremgiatn>{{cite web |url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1028229 |title=Aussies struggle in fog at Creekside |publisher=Nine MSN |location=Australia |date=March 2010 |accessdate=22 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322044953/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1028229 |archivedate=22 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the 2010 Winter Olympic Games, Dallas took a break from the sport,<ref name=motifivationalspeaker/> and had originally planned as a retirement that he announced before the 2010 Games.<ref name=plannedsomething>{{cite news |url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=975914 |title=Strong Aussie team named for Paralympics |publisher=Nine MSN |location=Australia |date=25 November 2009 |accessdate=22 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322045829/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=975914 |archivedate=22 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{2010 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dallas, Shannon}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Australian male alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2010 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic alpine skiers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Institute of Sport Paralympic skiers]]\n[[Category:New South Wales Institute of Sport alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian sit skier|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Shannon Dallas\n| image =File:090310 - Shannon Dallas at Vancouver 2010 Paralympics - 3b.jpg \n| caption =Shannon Dallas prior to the Vancouver 2010 Paralympic Games.\n| nationality = {{AUS}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1977|8|16}}\n| birth_place =  \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height =\n| weight =\n| country = Australia\n| sport = [[Para-alpine skiing]]\n| event = Downhill<br/>Super-G<br/>Giant slalom<br/>Slalom<br/>Super combined\n| collegeteam =\n| club = \n| worlds = \n| regionals = \n| nationals = \n| olympics = \n| paralympics = [[2010 Winter Paralympics]]\n| highestranking = \n| pb = \n| medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | [[Alpine skiing]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2009  High 1 Resort, Korea|Super G Sitting}}\n| imagesize =\n| fullname = \n| nicknames = \n}}\n'''Shannon Dallas''' (born 16 August 1977) is an Australian sit skier who receives support from the [[New South Wales Institute of Sport]]. Dallas participated in the [[2006 Winter Paralympics]] in [[Turin]], Italy, and the [[2010 Winter Paralympics]] in Vancouver, Canada.\n\n==Personal==\nBorn on 16 August 1977,<ref name=\"vancouver2010.paralympic.org.au\">{{cite web|url=http://vancouver2010.paralympic.org.au/team/shannon-dallas|title=Shannon Dallas|publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee|location=Australia|year=2010|accessdate=22 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815010941/http://vancouver2010.paralympic.org.au/team/shannon-dallas|archivedate=15 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dallas was a carpenter prior to an accident in 2000 where he broke his back<ref name=newspaper2/> after falling through a roof.<ref name=newspaper9>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Accident-free workers learn to keep it safe|newspaper=St Marys-Mt Druitt Star|location=Australia|date=29 November 2010|first=Kylie|last=Stevens|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:SMS8&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=137B3F729197EFD0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> He also used to be a surfie.<ref name=newspaper2/> When he was young, he moved around a lot.<ref name=newspaper4/> After finishing his [[Higher School Certificate (New South Wales)|HSC]], he moved to [[Toongabbie]] where he lived with a friend in a loungeroom.<ref name=newspaper4/> Dallas is from [[Terrigal]],<ref name=newspaper3>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Out of contention|newspaper=Central Coast Express Advocate|location=Sydney, Australia|date=24 March 2010|page=79|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12EA30831F947CE8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> New South Wales.<ref name=newspaper2/> He moved there in around 2003.<ref name=newspaper4/>\n\nDallas does work as a public speaker.<ref name=newspaper9/><ref name=crasssshhh/><ref name=motifivationalspeaker>{{cite news|url=http://www.bild.de/sport/mehr-sport/dallas/paralympic-star-will-lieber-liebe-statt-schnee-11892636.bild.html |title=Shannon Dallas: Paralympic-Athlet will lieber Liebe statt Schnee \u2013 Sport |location=Germany |language=de |publisher=Bild.de |date= |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> In 2010, he spoke at the [[Concord Library]] about his experiences with disability sport.<ref name=newspaper5/> That same year, he also spoke at [[Lend Lease Communities|Delfin Lend Lease]] about workplace safety.<ref name=newspaper9/>\n\nIn 2009 and 2010, Dallas worked in [[wheelchair basketball]] development on New South Wales's central coast. He also worked as a newspaper columnist.<ref name=crasssshhh/> In 2010, he played wheelchair basketball for the Sydney University Wheelkings.<ref name=crasssshhh/> He had four relationships in four years in the lead up to the 2010 Winter Paralympics. The demands of high level skiing was a factor in the relationships not working.<ref name=motifivationalspeaker/> In 2009, he had a shoulder reconstruction,<ref name=newspaper11/><ref name=newspaper1/> and other rehabilitation at the Mount Wilga Rehabilitation Hospital.<ref name=crasssshhh/> He also dealt with [[necrotising fasciitis]], a flesh-eating bug, that sidelined him for seven months.<ref name=newspaper2>{{Cite news|title=A battle against bugs and breaks|newspaper=The Courier Mail|location=Brisbane, Australia|date=18 March 2010|accessdate=22 October 2012|first=Amanda|last=Lulham|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACMB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E833A566DCB330&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9|page=79}}</ref><ref name=newspaper1/> The flesh-eating bug treatment involved a [[Skin grafting|skin graft]].<ref name=newspaper2/>\n\nDallas was featured on the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]'s ''X Paralympic Games'' in March 2010.<ref name=newspaper12>{{cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Critic's view Saturday, March 20|newspaper=The Age|location=Melbourne, Australia|date=18 March 2010|first=Conrad|last=Walters|page=32|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ASAB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E83CA4D9D812D8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref>\n\n==Skiing==\nDallas is a [[Monoski|sit-skier]].<ref name=motifivationalspeaker/><ref name=newspaper1/> When skiing, he can go {{convert|100|km}} an hour.<ref name=newspaper2/> He receives support from the [[New South Wales Institute of Sport]],<ref name=crasssshhh/><ref name=katelellis>{{cite web|url=http://www.health.gov.au/internet/ministers/publishing.nsf/Content/6B9704860CA28FAACA2576E3001850C2/$File/ke014.pdf|accessdate=24 October 2012|location=Australia|date=11 March 2010|first=Kate|last=Ellis|title=Winter Paralympians to inspire a nation|page=3|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229155208/http://www.health.gov.au/internet/ministers/publishing.nsf/Content/6B9704860CA28FAACA2576E3001850C2/$File/ke014.pdf|archivedate=29 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the [[Australian Institute of Sport]] and the Australian Government Sports Training Grants program.<ref name=katelellis>{{cite web|url=http://www.health.gov.au/internet/ministers/publishing.nsf/Content/6B9704860CA28FAACA2576E3001850C2/$File/ke014.pdf|accessdate=24 October 2012|location=Australia|date=11 March 2010|first=Kate|last=Ellis|title=Winter Paralympians to inspire a nation|page=3|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229155208/http://www.health.gov.au/internet/ministers/publishing.nsf/Content/6B9704860CA28FAACA2576E3001850C2/$File/ke014.pdf|archivedate=29 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2003, he competed at the [[Hartford Ski Spectacular]].<ref name=skiedthere>{{cite news |author=Ryan Slabaugh |url=http://www.vaildaily.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20031212/SPORTS/312120201 |title=Ryan Slabaugh |publisher=Vail Daily |date=12 December 2003 |location=Vail, Colorao |accessdate=22 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050120032543/http://www.vaildaily.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20031212%2FSPORTS%2F312120201 |archivedate=20 January 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> During the 2005/2006 World Cup skiing season, he had a second and third place finish in the giant slalom events.<ref name=withdrew/>\n[[File:210310 - Shannon Dallas slalom Vancouver Paralympics - 3b - crop.jpg|left|thumb|Shannon Dallas competing in the Slalom event at the Vancouver 2010 Paralympic Games.]]\nDallas competed at the [[2006 Winter Paralympics]],<ref name=newspaper4>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=ROOM FOR THOUGHT|newspaper=Central Coast Express Advocate |location=Sydney, Australia|date=7 May 2010|first=Nicole|last=Taylor|page=3|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1307E0F6F41D6A58&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> where he was the team captain. Coming into the Games, he was ranked in the top five in the world in the downhill and super-G.<ref name=withdrew/> While in Turin, his grandmother died.<ref name=newspaper11/> He finished ninth in the super-G and crashed in the downhill. Following his first run in the giant slalom, he was 34th with a time of 1:07.90. He climbed back to finish 18th overall in the giant slalom following his second run which had a time of 57.32 seconds. He withdrew from the Games before the slalom event, his last scheduled one.<ref name=withdrew>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/sport/skipper-quits-while-hes-ahead/2006/03/18/1142582578883.html |title=Skipper quits while he's ahead |publisher=The Age |location=Australia |date=18 March 2006 |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Dallas won a World Cup.<ref name=newspaper5>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Quicknews|newspaper=Inner West Courier&nbsp;\u2013 Inner West Edition|location=Sydney, Australia|date=22 June 2010 |page=3|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=137B3F729197EFD0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> In 2009, he won the World Championships for the super-G.<ref name=newspaper2/> He had a high speed crash at the 2009 IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships in Korea in the downhill event, which resulted in severe injuries that doctors thought might end his career.<ref name=newspaper2/><ref name=crasssshhh>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/team_info.cgi?client=0-4219-72986-0-8843498&sID=129341&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=8863337&sectionID=129341 |title=Gaetano, Shannon and Liesl updates |publisher=Sydney Uni WheelKings |date=17 April 2009 |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=horrowshow>{{cite web|first=Emma |last=Herd |url=http://express-advocate-wyong.whereilive.com.au/sport/story/dallas-makes-games-team-after-tough-year/ |title=Dallas makes Games team after tough year |publisher=Express Advocate Wyong Edition |location=Wyong, New South Wales |date= |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nDallas was officially named to the Australian 2010 Winter Paralympics team in November 2009.<ref name=officiallynamed>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/paralympic-team-for-vancover-sprinkled-with-experience/story-e6frg7mf-1225803724024 |title=Paralympic Team for Vancouver sprinkled with exaperience |publisher=The Australian |location=Australia |year=2009 |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref> A ceremony was held in Canberra with Australian Paralympic Committee president [[Greg Hartung]] and Minister for Sport [[Kate Ellis]] making the announcement.<ref name=makeannouncemnetellis>{{cite web|last=Browning |first=Jennifer |url=http://www.abc.net.au/sport/stories/2009/11/25/2753734.htm |title=Winter Paralympics team biggest yet |publisher=ABC Grandstand Sport |date=25 November 2009 |accessdate=24 October 2012 |location=Australia}}</ref> He and the rest of Australia's para-alpine team arrived in the Paralympic village on 9 March 2010.<ref name=arrivedvillage>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/australian-assault-on-paralympics-takes-shape-in-vancouver/story-fn4vwn8v-1225838309977 |title=Australian assault on Paralympics takes shape in Vancouver |first=Margie |last=McDonald |location=Australia |newspaper=The Australian |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref> At the Games, he competed in the super-G event, when he was the super-G world champion at the time.<ref name=newspaper1>{{Cite news|title=Aussie medal hopes left in tatters|newspaper=Sunday Telegraph |location=Sydney, Australia|date=21 March 2010|first=Amanda|last=Lulham|page=103|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ATLB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E833A566DCB330&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> In the super-G, he finished 12th.<ref name=newspaper1/> He also competed in the super combined,<ref name=newspaper1/> downhill and giant slalom events.<ref name=newspaper2/> He did not place in the super combined event as he failed to finish his second run<ref name=newspaper3/> because he crashed.<ref name=newspaper7>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Cam in double medal miracle|newspaper=Daily Telegraph |location=Sydney, Australia|date=22 March 2010|first=Amanda|last=Lulham|page=54|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ATLB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E98D657B94F9B8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref><ref name=newspaper7>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Gold double for skier|newspaper=Hobart Mercury|location=Australia|date=22 March 2010|first=Amanda|last=Lulham|page=44|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:AHMB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E9A7A95DEA14C0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref><ref name=newspaper8>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=AAP News: PARA: Rahles-Rahbula claims \"miracle\" second bronze|agency=AAP News |location=Australia|date=21 March 2010|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:WAAP&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E96A02D8DFE798&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> He had been sitting in the sixth spot after his first run and kept sixth spot after his second run.<ref name=newspaper11>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=Cold, wet weather a downer for Dallas|newspaper=Central Coast Express Advocate |location=Sydney, Australia|date=19 March 2010|first=Emma|last=Herd|page=77|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E88F0FD0F0DA60&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> He finished 11th in the super-G.<ref name=newspaper6>{{Cite news|accessdate=22 October 2012|title=WEEKEND SCOREBOARD|newspaper=The Australian|location=Australia|date=22 March 2010|page=40|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:AUSB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12E98D5A34AEDCB8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> He finished ninth in the super combined.<ref name=newspaper6/> He did not finish in the slalom.<ref name=newspaper6/> He overskied the giant slalom and finished sixth.<ref name=overskied>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-03-17/aussie-dallas-sixth-in-giant-slalom/368260 |title=Aussie Dallas sixth in giant slalom |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=17 March 2010 |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> The giant slalom course was difficult, and Dallas was one of only 30 out of 54 skiers to finish the course.<ref name=moremgiatn>{{cite web |url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1028229 |title=Aussies struggle in fog at Creekside |publisher=Nine MSN |location=Australia |date=March 2010 |accessdate=22 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322044953/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1028229 |archivedate=22 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the 2010 Winter Olympic Games, Dallas took a break from the sport,<ref name=motifivationalspeaker/> and had originally planned as a retirement that he announced before the 2010 Games.<ref name=plannedsomething>{{cite news |url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=975914 |title=Strong Aussie team named for Paralympics |publisher=Nine MSN |location=Australia |date=25 November 2009 |accessdate=22 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322045829/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=975914 |archivedate=22 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{2010 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dallas, Shannon}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Australian male alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2010 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic alpine skiers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Institute of Sport Paralympic skiers]]\n[[Category:New South Wales Institute of Sport alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_Dallas"}
{"title_page": "Dukwon High School", "text_new": "{{short description|High school in Daegu, South Korea}}\n{{Orphan|date=September 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Dukwon High School <br> \ub355\uc6d0\uace0\ub4f1\ud559\uad50 <br> \u5fb7\u5143\u9ad8\u7b49\u5b78\u6821\n| image = [[File:Dukwon_High_School_symbol.png|none|250px]]\n| motto = ''{{lang|la|Aim high and nourish force}}'' <br /><br />''{{lang|la|\ud070 \ub73b\uc744 \ud488\uace0 \ud798\uc744 \uae30\ub974\uc790}}''\n| established = 1978\n| type = [[Private school]]\n| head_name = Principal\n| head = Kyung-hak Seo (\uc11c\uacbd\ud559)\n| streetaddress = 37, Uksu-gil\n| city = [[Suseong-gu]]\n| state = [[Daegu]]\n| country = [[South Korea]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|35.825014|128.706372|type:edu_source:googlemaps_region:KR|display=inline,title}}\n| grades = 10-12\n| gender = [[Co-educational]]\n| class = approx. 30 students\n| students = approx. 1,150\n| faculty = approx. 85\n| ratio = approx. 15:1\n| newspaper = Dukwon\n| campus = [[Suburban]]\n| free_label = Tree\n| free = [[Zelkova]]\n| free_label2 = Song\n| free_2 = Untitled(Dukwon of Cradle)\n| free_label3 = Foundation\n| free_3 = ''Dukwon Education Foundation''\n| website = http://www.dukwon.hs.kr\n}}\n'''Dukwon High School''' (also known as '''Dukwon''', or '''Dukwon HS'''; [[Hangeul]]: \ub355\uc6d0\uace0\ub4f1\ud559\uad50, \ub355\uc6d0\uace0; [[Hanja]]: \u5fb7\u5143\u9ad8\u7b49\u5b78\u6821) is a private preparatory school in [[Suseong-gu]], [[Daegu]], [[South Korea]].  The school's motto is \"Aim high and nourish force\" and, its symbol is the [[zelkova]] tree.\nLike most schools in Korea, Dukwon High School starts its school year in March, starts its second semester in August, and ends the school year in February. There is a weeklong spring break in mid-February.\n\n==History==\n\n=== Origins ===\n[[File:Dr. Jin-won Kim.jpg|thumb|thumb|left|260px|Dr. Jin-won Kim, Founder]]\nOn August 24, 1978, Dr. Jin-won Kim was approved to establish a education foundation, Dukwon Education Foundation, and on February 28, 1980, the new school building was completed in [[Hwanggeum-dong,_Daegu|Hwanggeum-dong]], Suseong-gu, Daegu. On March 1 of 1980, the first Principal Byeong-sip Seo was inaugurated, and on March 5 the first freshman entered. At this time, 10 classes per grade were accredited and the number of classes continued to increase.\n21 years after the school was established, the plan to change the location was approved. The groundbreaking ceremony was held on April 27, 2001. On February 28, 2002, it was moved to 37, Uksu-gil, Suseong-gu, Daegu. In the same year, Cheongramsa ([[Hangeul]]: \uccad\ub78c\uc0ac; [[Hanja]]: \u9751\u85cd\u820d), dormitory was opened.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\n* [[Taeghwan Hyeon]] '80, chemist, director of [[Institute for Basic Science|IBS]], AE of [[Journal of the American Chemical Society|JACS]]\n* Jeong-su Kim '80, Lieutenant General, Commander of [[Republic of Korea Army Special Warfare Command]]\n* [[:ko:\ubc15\uacbd\ucca0|Kyung-cheol Park]] '80, doctor, writer of 'A Beautiful Walk with Rustic Doctor(\uc2dc\uace8\uc758\uc0ac\uc758 \uc544\ub984\ub2e4\uc6b4 \ub3d9\ud589)'\n* Seong-yong Youn '82, Director of [[National Folk Museum of Korea]]\n* An-su Park '83, Major General, Commander of The 39th Infantry Division(Republic of Korea)\n* [[:ko:\ud64d\uc9c0\ub9cc|Ji-man Hong]] '84, former journalist, former member of the [[National Assembly of the Republic of Korea]]\n* [[E Sens]](Min-ho Kang) 2003, rapper\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{Coord missing|South Korea}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1980]]\n[[Category:High schools in Daegu]]\n\n{{SouthKorea-school-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|High school in Daegu, South Korea}}\n{{Orphan|date=September 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Dukwon High School <br> \ub355\uc6d0\uace0\ub4f1\ud559\uad50 <br> \u5fb7\u5143\u9ad8\u7b49\u5b78\u6821\n| image = [[File:Dukwon_High_School_symbol.png|none|250px]]\n| motto = ''{{lang|la|Aim high and nourish force}}'' <br /><br />''{{lang|la|\ud070 \ub73b\uc744 \ud488\uace0 \ud798\uc744 \uae30\ub974\uc790}}''\n| established = 1978\n| type = [[Private school]]\n| head_name = Principal\n| head = Kyung-hak Seo (\uc11c\uacbd\ud559)\n| streetaddress = 37, Uksu-gil\n| city = [[Suseong-gu]]\n| state = [[Daegu]]\n| country = [[South Korea]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|35.825014|128.706372|type:edu_source:googlemaps_region:KR|display=inline,title}}\n| grades = 10-12\n| gender = [[Co-educational]]\n| class = approx. 30 students\n| students = approx. 1,150\n| faculty = approx. 85\n| ratio = approx. 15:1\n| newspaper = Dukwon\n| campus = [[Suburban]]\n| free_label = Tree\n| free = [[Zelkova]]\n| free_label2 = Song\n| free_2 = Untitled(Dukwon of Cradle)\n| free_label3 = Foundation\n| free_3 = ''Dukwon Education Foundation''\n| website = http://www.dukwon.hs.kr\n}}\n'''Dukwon High School''' (also known as '''Dukwon''', or '''Dukwon HS'''; [[Hangeul]]: \ub355\uc6d0\uace0\ub4f1\ud559\uad50, \ub355\uc6d0\uace0; [[Hanja]]: \u5fb7\u5143\u9ad8\u7b49\u5b78\u6821) is a private preparatory school in [[Suseong-gu]], [[Daegu]], [[South Korea]].  The school's motto is \"Aim high and nourish force\" and, its symbol is the [[zelkova]] tree.\nLike most schools in Korea, Dukwon High School starts its school year in March, starts its second semester in August, and ends the school year in February. There is a weeklong spring break in mid-February.\n\n==History==\n\n=== Origins ===\n[[File:Dr. Jin-won Kim.jpg|thumb|thumb|left|260px|Dr. Jin-won Kim, Founder]]\nOn August 24, 1978, Dr. Jin-won Kim was approved to establish a education foundation, Dukwon Education Foundation, and on February 28, 1980, the new school building was completed in [[Hwanggeum-dong,_Daegu|Hwanggeum-dong]], Suseong-gu, Daegu. On March 1 of 1980, the first Principal Byeong-sip Seo was inaugurated, and on March 5 the first freshman entered. At this time, 10 classes per grade were accredited and the number of classes continued to increase.\n21 years after the school was established, the plan to change the location was approved. The groundbreaking ceremony was held on April 27, 2001. On February 28, 2002, it was moved to 37, Uksu-gil, Suseong-gu, Daegu. In the same year, Cheongramsa ([[Hangeul]]: \uccad\ub78c\uc0ac; [[Hanja]]: \u9751\u85cd\u820d), dormitory was opened.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\n* [[Taeghwan Hyeon]] '80, chemist, director of [[Institute for Basic Science|IBS]], AE of [[Journal of the American Chemical Society|JACS]]\n* Jeong-su Kim '80, Lieutenant General, Commander of [[Republic of Korea Army Special Warfare Command]]\n* [[:ko:\ubc15\uacbd\ucca0|Kyung-cheol Park]] '80, doctor, writer of 'A Beautiful Walk with Rustic Doctor(\uc2dc\uace8\uc758\uc0ac\uc758 \uc544\ub984\ub2e4\uc6b4 \ub3d9\ud589)'\n* Seong-yong Youn '82, Director of [[National Folk Museum of Korea]]\n* An-su Park '83, Major General, Commander of The 39th Infantry Division(Republic of Korea)\n* [[:ko:\ud64d\uc9c0\ub9cc|Ji-man Hong]] '84, former journalist, former member of the [[National Assembly of the Republic of Korea]]\n* [[E Sens]](Min-ho Kang) '03, rapper\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{Coord missing|South Korea}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1980]]\n[[Category:High schools in Daegu]]\n\n{{SouthKorea-school-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Korhistorystudy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable alumni", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dukwon_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Creepiness", "text_new": "{{wiktionary|creepy|eerie}}\n{{Other uses|Creepy (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Creepiness''' is the state of being [[wikt:creepy|creepy]], or causing an unpleasant feeling of [[fear]] or [[wikt:unease|unease]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thesocietypages.org/socimages/2015/12/26/what-is-creepiness/|title=What is \"creepiness\"? - Sociological Images|first=The Society|last=Pages|website=thesocietypages.org}}</ref> A person who exhibits creepy behaviour is called a '''creep'''. Certain traits or hobbies may make people seem creepy to others. The internet has been described as increasingly creepy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/cultural-comment/the-age-of-creepiness|title=The Age of Creepiness|website=The New Yorker}}</ref> [[Adam Kotsko]] has compared the modern conception of creepiness to the [[Freudian]] concept of ''[[unheimlich]]''. The term has also been used to describe [[paranormal]] or [[supernatural]] phenomena.\n\n==History and studies==\nIn the abstract the feeling of \"creepiness\" is subjective: for example some [[dolls]] have been described as creepy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/69472/what-creepiness|title=What is 'Creepiness'?|date=6 October 2015 |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 20th century, association was made between [[involuntary celibacy]] and creepiness.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=yEJcGQAACAAJ |title=Blueprint for a Higher Civilization |first=Henry |last=Flynt |year=1975 |quote=In 1961-1962, I tried to develop a theory of the creep problem. This theory took involuntary celibacy as the defining characteristic of the creep.}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of creepiness has only recently been formally addressed in [[social media marketing]].<ref> {{cite book |year=2017 |first1=Bikramjit |last1=Rishi |first2=Subir |last2=Bandyopadhyay |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=epcuDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT195 |page=195 |title=Contemporary Issues in Social Media Marketing |isbn=978-1317193982 |quote=In this chapter, we define creepiness and discuss how privacy and perceived creepiness differ. Then, we explain why creepiness matters and provide recommendations to minimize the negative effect of perceived creepiness on customer}}</ref>\n\n==Causes==\nThe state of creepiness has been associated with \u201cfeeling scared, nervous, anxious or worried\u201d, \u201cawkward or uncomfortable\u201d, \u201cvulnerable or violated\u201d in a study conducted by Watt et al. <ref name=\"Watt\">Watt M. C., Maitland R. A., Gallagher C. E. (2017): A Case of the \u201cHeeby Jeebies\u201d: An Examination of Intuitive Judgements of \u201cCreepiness\u201d, Canadian Journal of Behavioural Science, Vol.49, n.1</ref>{{rp|61}} This state arises in the presence of a creepy element, which can be an individual or, as recently observed, new technologies.\n\n===Individuals===\nCreepiness can be caused by the appearance of an individual. \nA study by McAndrew et al. <ref name=\"McA\">McAndrew F. T., Koehnke S. S. (2016): On the nature of creepiness, New Ideas in Psychology, Vol.4</ref> investigated the characteristics that make people creepy. Creepy people were thought to be more often male than female by an overwhelming majority of participants (around 95% of both males and females participants).<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|12}}  Another study conducted by Watt et al. also found that participants associated the [[ectomorphic]] body type (more linear) with creepiness, more than the other two body types (51% vs [[mesomorphic]], 24% and [[endomorphic]], 23%). Other cues of creepiness included low hygiene, especially according to female participants, and a dishevelled appearance .  Participants also identified the face as an area with potentially creepy features: in particular the eyes and the teeth.  Both of those physical features were deemed creepy not only for their unpleasant appearance (ex. squinty eyes or crooked teeth) but also for the movements and expressions they engaged it (ex. darting eye movements and odd smiles).<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|61}}  \n\nIn fact, appearance doesn\u2019t seem to be the only factor making an individual creepy: behaviours provide cues as well.<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|58}} Behaviours such as \u201cbeing unusually quiet and staring (34%), following or lurking (15%), behaving abnormally (21%), or in a socially awkward, \"sketchy\" or suspicious way (20%)\u201d are all contributing to a feeling of creepiness, as described by Watt et al.\u2019s study.<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|61}}\n  \n=== Technology ===\nIn addition to other individuals, new technologies, such as marketing\u2019s targeted ads and AI, have been qualified as creepy.\n\nA study by Moore et al <ref name=\"Moore\">Moore R. S., Moore M. L., Shanahan K. J., Horky A., Mack B.(2015): Creepy marketing: three dimensions of perceived excessive online privacy violation, Marketing Management Journal, Vol.25</ref> described what aspect of marketing participants considered creepy. The main three reasons are the following: using invasive tactics, causing discomfort and violating of norms. Invasive tactics are practiced by marketers that know so much about the consumer that the ads are \u201ccreepily\u201d personalised. Secondly, some ads create discomfort by making the consumer question \u201cthe motives of the company advertising the product\u201d. Finally, some ads violate social norms by having inappropriate content, for example by unnecessarily sexualizing it.<ref name=\"Moore\" />{{rp|48}}\n\nIt is marketing\u2019s extensive knowledge used in an improper way, together with a certain loss of control over our data, that creates a feeling of creepiness.<ref name=\"Moore\" />{{rp|44}} \n\nAnother creepy aspect of technology is human looking AI: this phenomenon is called the [[uncanny valley]].\n\nHumans find robots creepy when they start closely resembling humans. It has been hypothesised that the reason why they are viewed as creepy is because they violate our notion of how a robot should look. A study focusing on children's responses to this phenomenon found evidence to support the hypothesis.<ref>Brink K. A., Gray K. and Wellman H.M. (2019): Creepiness Creeps In: Uncanny Valley Feelings Are Acquired in Childhood, Child Dev, Vol.90</ref>{{rp|1210}}\n\n==Evolutionary explanation==\nSeveral studies have hypothesized that creepiness is an evolutionary response to potentially dangerous situations.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|10}}   It could be linked to a mechanism called [[agency detection]] which makes individuals expect malignant agents to be responsible for small changes in our environment. McAndrew et al. illustrates the idea with the example of a person hearing some noises while walking in a dark alley. That person would go in high alert, fearing that some dangerous individual was there. If that wasn\u2019t the case the loss would be small. If, on the other hand, a dangerous individual was actually in the alley and the person had not been alerted by this creepy feeling, the loss could have been significant.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|11}} \n\nCreepiness would therefore serve the purpose of alerting us in situations in which the danger isn\u2019t outright obvious but rather ambiguous. In this case, ambiguity both refers to the possible presence of a threat and to its nature, sexual or physical for example.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|10}} Creepiness \u201cmay reside in between the unknowing and the fear\u201d<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|58}} in the sense that individuals experiencing it are unsure if there truly is something to fear or not. Truth is that creepy characteristics are not simply caused by threat potential: in fact, [[ectomorphic]] body types are not the most powerful bodies and facial expressions are not a proxy of physical strength either.<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|63}} Therefore, creepiness isn\u2019t only related to how threatening a characteristic is, in the sense of how dangerous and strong the individual can be. There are more facets to consider.\n\nAnother characteristic of creepiness is unpredictable behaviour.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|12}} Unpredictability links back to this idea of ambiguity.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|11}} When an individual is unpredictable it isn\u2019t possible to tell when his behaviour will turn violent: this adds to the ambiguity of a potentially dangerous situation. This theory is endorsed by studies. Not only is unpredictability directly listed as a creepy characteristic<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|13}}, but other behaviours, such as norm-breaking behaviours are indirectly linked with unpredictability. Such behaviours show that the individual doesn\u2019t conform to some social standards we would expect in a given situation. <ref name=\"Leander\">Leander N. P., Chartrand T. L., Bargh J. A. (2012): You give me the chills: Embodied reactions to inappropriate amounts of behavioral mimicry, Psychological Science, Vol.23</ref>{{rp|773}}  For example, we previously mentioned staring at strangers or lack of hygiene: those are behaviours that make us uneasy, creeped out, because they don\u2019t fit the norm and therefore we don\u2019t expect them. More generally, participants tended to define creepiness as \u201cdifferent\u201d in the sense of not behaving, or looking, socially acceptable.<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|62}} Such differences point towards a \u201csocial mismatch\u201d.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|10}} \n\nHumans have a natural system of detection of such mismatch: a physical feeling of coldness.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|10}} When an individual is creeped out, they report feeling those \u201ccold chills\u201d. This phenomenon has been studied by Leander et al, with relation to nonverbal mimicry in social interactions, meaning the unintentional copying of another\u2019s behaviour. Inappropriate mimicry may leave a person feeling like something is off about the other.<ref name=\"Leander\" />{{rp|772}} Absence of non-verbal mimicry in a friendly interaction, or the presence of it in a professional setting, raises suspicion as it doesn\u2019t follow the norms. Individuals are left wondering what other unusual behaviour the other might engage in.<ref name=\"Leander\" />{{rp|773}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Social skills]]\n* [[Uncanny valley]]\n* [[Internet privacy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===General citations===\n* {{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/?id=6v9JBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT23&dq=creepiness#v=onepage |title= Creepiness |authorlink= Adam Kotsko |first= Adam |last=Kotsko |publisher= John Hunt Publishing |year=2015 |isbn= 9781782798453 }}\n\n[[Category:Fear]]\n[[Category:Feeling]]\n[[Category:Emotions]]\n[[Category:Social media]]\n\n{{sociology-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{wiktionary|creepy|eerie}}\n{{Other uses|Creepy (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Creepiness''' is the state of being [[wikt:creepy|creepy]], or causing an unpleasant feeling of [[fear]] or [[wikt:unease|unease]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thesocietypages.org/socimages/2015/12/26/what-is-creepiness/|title=What is \"creepiness\"? - Sociological Images|first=The Society|last=Pages|website=thesocietypages.org}}</ref> A person who exhibits creepy behaviour is called a '''creep'''. Certain traits or hobbies may make people seem creepy to others. The internet has been described as increasingly creepy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/cultural-comment/the-age-of-creepiness|title=The Age of Creepiness|website=The New Yorker}}</ref> [[Adam Kotsko]] has compared the modern conception of creepiness to the [[Freudian]] concept of ''[[unheimlich]]''. The term has also been used to describe [[paranormal]] or [[supernatural]] phenomena.\n\n==History and studies==\nIn the abstract the feeling of \"creepiness\" is subjective: for example some [[dolls]] have been described as creepy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/69472/what-creepiness|title=What is 'Creepiness'?|date=6 October 2015 |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 20th century, association was made between [[involuntary celibacy]] and creepiness.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=yEJcGQAACAAJ |title=Blueprint for a Higher Civilization |first=Henry |last=Flynt |year=1975 |quote=In 1961-1962, I tried to develop a theory of the creep problem. This theory took involuntary celibacy as the defining characteristic of the creep.}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of creepiness has only recently been formally addressed in [[social media marketing]].<ref> {{cite book |year=2017 |first1=Bikramjit |last1=Rishi |first2=Subir |last2=Bandyopadhyay |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=epcuDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT195 |page=195 |title=Contemporary Issues in Social Media Marketing |isbn=978-1317193982 |quote=In this chapter, we define creepiness and discuss how privacy and perceived creepiness differ. Then, we explain why creepiness matters and provide recommendations to minimize the negative effect of perceived creepiness on customer}}</ref>\n\n==Causes==\nThe state of creepiness has been associated with \u201cfeeling scared, nervous, anxious or worried\u201d, \u201cawkward or uncomfortable\u201d, \u201cvulnerable or violated\u201d in a study conducted by Watt et al. <ref name=\"Watt\">Watt M. C., Maitland R. A., Gallagher C. E. (2017): A Case of the \u201cHeeby Jeebies\u201d: An Examination of Intuitive Judgements of \u201cCreepiness\u201d, Canadian Journal of Behavioural Science, Vol.49, n.1</ref>{{rp|61}} This state arises in the presence of a creepy element, which can be an individual or, as recently observed, new technologies.\n\n===Individuals===\nCreepiness can be caused by the appearance of an individual. \nA study by McAndrew et al. <ref name=\"McA\">McAndrew F. T., Koehnke S. S. (2016): On the nature of creepiness, New Ideas in Psychology, Vol.4</ref> investigated the characteristics that make people creepy. Creepy people were thought to be more often male than female by an overwhelming majority of participants (around 95% of both males and females participants).<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|12}}  Another study conducted by Watt et al. also found that participants associated the [[ectomorphic]] body type (more linear) with creepiness, more than the other two body types (51% vs [[mesomorphic]], 24% and [[endomorphic]], 23%). Other cues of creepiness included low hygiene, especially according to female participants, and a dishevelled appearance .  Participants also identified the face as an area with potentially creepy features: in particular the eyes and the teeth.  Both of those physical features were deemed creepy not only for their unpleasant appearance (ex. squinty eyes or crooked teeth) but also for the movements and expressions they engaged it (ex. darting eye movements and odd smiles).<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|61}}  \n\nIn fact, appearance doesn\u2019t seem to be the only factor making an individual creepy: behaviours provide cues as well.<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|58}} Behaviours such as \u201cbeing unusually quiet and staring (34%), following or lurking (15%), behaving abnormally (21%), or in a socially awkward, \"sketchy\" or suspicious way (20%)\u201d are all contributing to a feeling of creepiness, as described by Watt et al.\u2019s study.<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|61}}\n  \n\n\n=== Technology ===\nIn addition to other individuals, new technologies, such as marketing\u2019s targeted ads and AI, have been qualified as creepy.\n\nA study by Moore et al <ref name=\"Moore\">Moore R. S., Moore M. L., Shanahan K. J., Horky A., Mack B.(2015): Creepy marketing: three dimensions of perceived excessive online privacy violation, Marketing Management Journal, Vol.25</ref> described what aspect of marketing participants considered creepy. The main three reasons are the following: using invasive tactics, causing discomfort and violating of norms. Invasive tactics are practiced by marketers that know so much about the consumer that the ads are \u201ccreepily\u201d personalised. Secondly, some ads create discomfort by making the consumer question \u201cthe motives of the company advertising the product\u201d. Finally, some ads violate social norms by having inappropriate content, for example by unnecessarily sexualizing it.<ref name=\"Moore\" />{{rp|48}}\n\nIt is marketing\u2019s extensive knowledge used in an improper way, together with a certain loss of control over our data, that creates a feeling of creepiness.<ref name=\"Moore\" />{{rp|44}} \n\n\nAnother creepy aspect of technology is human looking AI: this phenomenon is called the [[uncanny valley]].\n\nHumans find robots creepy when they start closely resembling humans. It has been hypothesised that the reason why they are viewed as creepy is because they violate our notion of how a robot should look. A study focusing on children's responses to this phenomenon found evidence to support the hypothesis.<ref>Brink K. A., Gray K. and Wellman H.M. (2019): Creepiness Creeps In: Uncanny Valley Feelings Are Acquired in Childhood, Child Dev, Vol.90</ref>{{rp|1210}}\n\n\n==Evolutionary explanation==\nSeveral studies have hypothesized that creepiness is an evolutionary response to potentially dangerous situations.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|10}}   It could be linked to a mechanism called [[agency detection]] which makes individuals expect malignant agents to be responsible for small changes in our environment. McAndrew et al. illustrates the idea with the example of a person hearing some noises while walking in a dark alley. That person would go in high alert, fearing that some dangerous individual was there. If that wasn\u2019t the case the loss would be small. If, on the other hand, a dangerous individual was actually in the alley and the person had not been alerted by this creepy feeling, the loss could have been significant.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|11}} \n\nCreepiness would therefore serve the purpose of alerting us in situations in which the danger isn\u2019t outright obvious but rather ambiguous. In this case, ambiguity both refers to the possible presence of a threat and to its nature, sexual or physical for example.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|10}} Creepiness \u201cmay reside in between the unknowing and the fear\u201d<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|58}} in the sense that individuals experiencing it are unsure if there truly is something to fear or not. Truth is that creepy characteristics are not simply caused by threat potential: in fact, [[ectomorphic]] body types are not the most powerful bodies and facial expressions are not a proxy of physical strength either.<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|63}} Therefore, creepiness isn\u2019t only related to how threatening a characteristic is, in the sense of how dangerous and strong the individual can be. There are more facets to consider.\n\nAnother characteristic of creepiness is unpredictable behaviour.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|12}} Unpredictability links back to this idea of ambiguity.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|11}} When an individual is unpredictable it isn\u2019t possible to tell when his behaviour will turn violent: this adds to the ambiguity of a potentially dangerous situation. This theory is endorsed by studies. Not only is unpredictability directly listed as a creepy characteristic<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|13}}, but other behaviours, such as norm-breaking behaviours are indirectly linked with unpredictability. Such behaviours show that the individual doesn\u2019t conform to some social standards we would expect in a given situation. <ref name=\"Leander\">Leander N. P., Chartrand T. L., Bargh J. A. (2012): You give me the chills: Embodied reactions to inappropriate amounts of behavioral mimicry, Psychological Science, Vol.23</ref>{{rp|773}}  For example, we previously mentioned staring at strangers or lack of hygiene: those are behaviours that make us uneasy, creeped out, because they don\u2019t fit the norm and therefore we don\u2019t expect them. More generally, participants tended to define creepiness as \u201cdifferent\u201d in the sense of not behaving, or looking, socially acceptable.<ref name=\"Watt\" />{{rp|62}} Such differences point towards a \u201csocial mismatch\u201d.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|10}} \n\nHumans have a natural system of detection of such mismatch: a physical feeling of coldness.<ref name=\"McA\" />{{rp|10}} When an individual is creeped out, they report feeling those \u201ccold chills\u201d. This phenomenon has been studied by Leander et al, with relation to nonverbal mimicry in social interactions, meaning the unintentional copying of another\u2019s behaviour. Inappropriate mimicry may leave a person feeling like something is off about the other.<ref name=\"Leander\" />{{rp|772}} Absence of non-verbal mimicry in a friendly interaction, or the presence of it in a professional setting, raises suspicion as it doesn\u2019t follow the norms. Individuals are left wondering what other unusual behaviour the other might engage in.<ref name=\"Leander\" />{{rp|773}}\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[Social skills]]\n* [[Uncanny valley]]\n* [[Internet privacy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===General citations===\n* {{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/?id=6v9JBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT23&dq=creepiness#v=onepage |title= Creepiness |authorlink= Adam Kotsko |first= Adam |last=Kotsko |publisher= John Hunt Publishing |year=2015 |isbn= 9781782798453 }}\n\n[[Category:Fear]]\n[[Category:Feeling]]\n[[Category:Emotions]]\n[[Category:Social media]]\n\n{{sociology-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Winston Kaminsky", "label": "safe", "comment": "- a lot of empty spaces", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creepiness"}
{"title_page": "Sensibility Objectified", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n|name          = Sensibility Objectified: The Sculptures of Sarbari Roy Choudhury\n|title_orig    =\n|translator    =\n|image         = Sensibility Objectified.jpg|caption       =\n|author        = [[R. Siva Kumar]]\n|illustrator   =\n|cover_artist  =\n|country       = [[India]]\n|language      = English\n|series        =\n|subject       = Art\n|genre         =\n|publisher     = Mapin Publishing\n|pub_date      = February 16, 2010\n|english_pub_date =\n|pages         = 136 \n|isbn          = 1890206032\n|oclc          =\n|preceded_by   =\n|followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''Sensibility Objectified: The Sculptures of Sarbari Roy Choudhury''''' is a book by [[R. Siva Kumar]] that discusses the life and sculptures of [[Sarbari Roy Choudhury]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sensibility-Objectified-Scluptures-Sarbari-Choudhury/dp/1890206032|title=Sensibility Objectified: The Sculptures of Sarbari Roy Choudhury|first=Siva R.|last=Kumar|date=16 February 2010|publisher=Mapin Publishing Gp Pty Ltd|via=Amazon}}</ref>\nAccording to [[R. Siva kumar]] the 'sculptural sensibility' of [[Sarbari Roy Choudhury]], represented in his figurative and animated works, reveals the artist\u2019s connection with the Indian traditions of sculpture, despite being strongly influenced by the West.\n\nSome of Roy's best works are of classical musicians\u2014[[Bade Ghulam Ali Khan]], [[Ali Akbar Khan]], [[Siddheshwari Devi]] and [[Kesarbai Kerkar]]. Starting from the 1950s, the monograph traces his work of each decade, revealing the artistic journey of one of India\u2019s leading sculptors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapinpub.in/bookinfo.php?id=189#visit|title=Sensibility Objectified|website=mapinpub.in}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Art history books]]\n[[Category:Books by R. Siva Kumar]]\n[[Category:Works about art genres]]\n[[Category:Works about ideologies]]\n[[Category:2010 non-fiction books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n|name          = Sensibility Objectified: The Sculptures of Sarbari Roy Choudhury\n|title_orig    =\n|translator    =\n|image         = Sensibility Objectified.jpg|caption       =\n|author        = [[R. Siva Kumar]]\n|illustrator   =\n|cover_artist  =\n|country       = [[India]]\n|language      = English\n|series        =\n|subject       = Art\n|genre         =\n|publisher     = Mapin Publishing\n|pub_date      = February 16, 2010\n|english_pub_date =\n|pages         = 136 \n|isbn          = 1890206032\n|oclc          =\n|preceded_by   =\n|followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''Sensibility Objectified: The Sculptures of Sarbari Roy Choudhury''''' is a book by [[R. Siva Kumar]] that discusses the life and sculptures of [[Sarbari Roy Choudhury]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sensibility-Objectified-Scluptures-Sarbari-Choudhury/dp/1890206032|title=Sensibility Objectified: The Scupltures of Sarbari Roy Choudhury|first=Siva R.|last=Kumar|date=16 February 2010|publisher=Mapin Publishing Gp Pty Ltd|via=Amazon}}</ref>\nAccording to [[R. Siva kumar]] the 'sculptural sensibility' of [[Sarbari Roy Choudhury]], represented in his figurative and animated works, reveals the artist\u2019s connection with the Indian traditions of sculpture, despite being strongly influenced by the West.\n\nSome of Roy's best works are of classical musicians\u2014[[Bade Ghulam Ali Khan]], [[Ali Akbar Khan]], [[Siddheshwari Devi]] and [[Kesarbai Kerkar]]. Starting from the 1950s, the monograph traces his work of each decade, revealing the artistic journey of one of India\u2019s leading sculptors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapinpub.in/bookinfo.php?id=189#visit|title=Sensibility Objectified|website=mapinpub.in}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Art history books]]\n[[Category:Books by R. Siva Kumar]]\n[[Category:Works about art genres]]\n[[Category:Works about ideologies]]\n[[Category:2010 non-fiction books]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensibility_Objectified"}
{"title_page": "John Cooke (Royal Navy officer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name = John Cooke\n| image = Captain John Cooke, 1763-1805.jpg\n| caption = John Cooke, painted c. 1797{{ndash}}1803 by [[Lemuel Francis Abbott]]\n| image_size = 300px\n| birth_date = 17 February 1762\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1805|10|21|1762|2|17|df=yes}}\n| placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n| placeofburial = \n| birth_place = [[Tenterground#London|Spitalfields Tenterground]], [[London]]\n| death_place = {{HMS|Bellerophon|1786|6}} off [[Cape Trafalgar]]\n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname = \n| allegiance = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| branch = [[File:Naval Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg|22px]] [[Royal Navy]]\n| serviceyears = 1776{{ndash}}1805\n| rank = [[Captain (Royal Navy)|Captain]]\n| unit = \n| commands = {{Plainlist|\n*{{HMS|Incendiary|1782|6}}\n*{{HMS|Monarch|1765|6}}\n*{{HMS|Nymphe|1780|6}}\n*{{HMS|Amethyst|1799|6}}\n*{{HMS|Bellerophon|1786|6}}\n}}\n| battles = \n*[[American War of Independence]]\n**[[Battle of Rhode Island]]\n*[[French Revolutionary Wars]]\n**[[Glorious First of June]]\n**Capture of [[French ship R\u00e9sistance|''R\u00e9sistance'']] & [[French ship Constance|''Constance'']]\n**Capture of {{Ship|French frigate|D\u00e9daigneuse|1797|2}}\n*[[Napoleonic Wars]]\n**[[Battle of Trafalgar]]{{KIA}}\n| awards = \n| relations = \n| laterwork = \n}}\n'''John Cooke''' (17 February 1762 {{ndash}} 21 October 1805) was an experienced and highly regarded officer of the [[Royal Navy]] during the [[American War of Independence]], the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] and the first years of the [[Napoleonic Wars]]. Cooke is best known for his death in hand-to-hand combat with French forces during the [[Battle of Trafalgar]] in 1805. During the action, his ship {{HMS|Bellerophon|1786|6}} was badly damaged and boarded by sailors and marines from the French [[ship of the line]] {{Ship|French ship|Aigle|1800|2}}. Cooke was killed in the ensuing melee, but his crew successfully drove off their opponents and ultimately forced the surrender of ''Aigle''.\n\nAside from his death, remarkably little is known of Cooke's circumstances, as unlike many of his fellow officers, Cooke was never a notable society figure. He was however well respected in his profession and following his death was the subject of tributes from officers who had served alongside him. Memorials to him were placed in [[St Paul's Cathedral]] and his local church in [[Wiltshire]].\n\n==Early life==\nJohn Cooke was baptised on 5 March 1762 at [[St. Mary, Whitechapel]], the second son of Francis Cooke, an [[Admiralty]] clerk, and his wife Margaret.{{r|\"NT:95\"}}{{Ref label|A|a|none}} John Cooke first went to sea at the age of eleven aboard the [[cutter (boat)|cutter]] {{HMS|Greyhound|1763|6}} under Lieutenant [[John Bazely]], before going ashore to spend time at Mr Braken's naval academy at [[Greenwich]]. He was entered onto the books of one of the [[royal yacht]]s by [[Alexander Hood, 1st Viscount Bridport|Sir Alexander Hood]], who would become an enduring patron of Cooke's.{{r|\"NT:95\"}} In 1776 he obtained a position as a [[midshipman]] on the [[ship of the line]] {{HMS|Eagle|1774|6}}, aged thirteen.{{r|\"CW:48\"}} Cooke served aboard ''Eagle'', the flagship of the [[North American Station]], during the next three years, seeing extensive action along the eastern seaboard. Notable among these actions were the naval operations around the [[Battle of Rhode Island]] in 1778, when ''Eagle'' was closely engaged with American units ashore.{{r|\"ODNB\"}} He distinguished himself in the assault, causing Admiral [[Richard Howe, 1st Earl Howe|Lord Howe]] to remark \"Why, young man, you wish to become a Lieutenant before you are of sufficient age.\"{{r|\"NT:95\"}} On 21 January 1779, Cooke was promoted to [[lieutenant]] and joined {{HMS|Superb|1760|6}} in the East Indies under [[Edward Hughes (Royal Navy officer)|Sir Edward Hughes]], but was forced to take a leave of absence due to ill-health.{{r|\"NT:95\"}}\n\nCooke returned to England and then went to France to spend a year studying, before rejoining the navy in 1782 with an appointment to the 90-gun {{HMS|Duke|1777|6}} under Captain [[Alan Gardner, 1st Baron Gardner|Alan Gardner]].{{r|\"NT:95\"}} Cooke saw action at the [[Battle of the Saintes]], at which ''Duke'' was heavily engaged. He remained with Gardner following the signing of the [[Treaty of Paris (1783)|Treaty of Paris]] in 1783, bringing an end to the American War of Independence, and served as his first-lieutenant aboard his next command, the 50-gun {{HMS|Europa|1783|6}}.{{r|\"NT:95\"}} Gardner became commodore at [[Jamaica]], flying his [[broad pennant]] aboard ''Europa'' and retaining Cooke as his first-lieutenant until Cooke was injured in a bad fall and had to be invalided home.{{r|\"NT:95\"}} He had recovered sufficiently by the time of the [[Spanish Armament]] in 1790 to be able to take up an appointment from his old patron, Sir Alexander Hood, to be third-lieutenant of his flagship, the 90-gun {{HMS|London|1766|6}}.{{r|\"NT:95\"}}{{r|\"ODNB\"}} When the crisis passed without breaking into open war, ''London'' was paid off and Cooke went ashore.{{r|\"NT:95\"}}\n\n==Frigate command==\nWith the outbreak of the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] in February 1793, Cooke rejoined Hood and became first-lieutenant of his new flagship, the 100-gun {{HMS|Royal George|1788|6}}, part of the [[Channel Fleet]]. On 21 February 1794, Cooke was promoted to [[commander]] and given his first independent command, the small [[fireship]] {{HMS|Incendiary|1782|6}}. Three months later, ''Incendiary'' was a signal repeater for the Channel Fleet during the [[Atlantic campaign of May 1794]], relaying [[Richard Howe, 1st Earl Howe|Lord Howe's]] signals to the fleet and operating as a scout in the search for the French fleet under [[Villaret de Joyeuse]]. On 1 June 1794, Cooke was a witness to the battle of the [[Glorious First of June]], although his tiny ship was far too small to engage in combat.{{r|\"JW1:126\"}} In the action's aftermath, Cooke was included in the general promotions issued to the fleet, becoming a [[post captain]] on 23 July 1794. For a year, Cooke was stationed off [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] as [[flag captain]] to [[James Wallace (Royal Navy officer)|Sir James Wallace]] aboard the 74-gun {{HMS|Monarch|1765|6}}, before returning to Britain and being offered command of the 28-gun {{HMS|Tourterelle|1795|6}}.{{r|\"NT:96\"}} Cooke accepted, but when he found out she was ordered to the West Indies, he resigned it, having been told by Gardner that further service in the West Indies would likely kill him.{{r|\"NT:96\"}}\n\nInstead in early 1796 he took command of the 36-gun [[frigate]] {{HMS|Nymphe|1780|6}}. ''Nymphe'' was employed in the blockade of the French Atlantic ports over the next year, and on 9 March 1797 was in company with {{HMS|St Fiorenzo|1794|6}} when they encountered the returning ships of a short-lived [[Battle of Fishguard|French invasion attempt]] of Britain that had been defeated at [[Fishguard]] in [[Wales]].{{r|\"JW2:80\"}} The French ships attempted to escape into [[Brest, France|Brest]], but were hunted down by the British, who forced the surrender of [[French ship R\u00e9sistance|''R\u00e9sistance'']] and [[French ship Constance|''Constance'']] in turn after successive short engagements.{{r|\"JH:45\"}} Neither of the British ships suffered a single casualty in the combat, and both French ships were subsequently purchased into the Royal Navy, bringing [[prize money]] to Cooke and his crew.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=14035|page=764|date=8 August 1797}}</ref>\n\nDespite this success, Cooke was unpopular with his men due to the strict discipline he enforced aboard his ship. This was graphically demonstrated just two months after the action off Brest, when ''Nymphe'' became embroiled in the [[Spithead and Nore mutinies|Spithead mutiny]]. Cooke attempted to assist Admiral [[John Colpoys]] at the mutiny's outbreak, and was ordered ashore by his crew when he tried to return to his ship. Cooke was tactfully removed from command by the Admiralty following the mutiny, although he was returned to service two years later aboard the new frigate {{HMS|Amethyst|1799|6}} in preparation for the Anglo-Russian invasion of the [[Batavian Republic]].{{r|\"CW:48\"}} During the invasion, ''Amethyst'' conveyed the [[Prince Frederick, Duke of York and Albany|Duke of York]] to the Netherlands and later participated in the evacuation of the force following the campaign's collapse.{{r|\"NT:96\"}}\n\nCooke was involved in operations in [[Quiberon Bay]] during the remainder of 1799, and in 1800 participated in an abortive invasion of [[Ferrol, Spain|Ferrol]]. During this time, ''Amethyst'' captured six French merchant ships and small privateers.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15301|page=1176|date=11 October 1800}}</ref> During 1801, Cooke participated in the capture of the {{Ship|French frigate|D\u00e9daigneuse|1797|2|up=yes}} off [[Cape Finisterre]], helping [[Samuel Hood Linzee]] and [[Sir Richard King, 2nd Baronet|Richard King]] chase her down on 26 January. ''Amethyst'' was not heavily engaged with ''D\u00e9daigneuse'' and received no damage, but aided in pursuing and trapping the French ship so that she could be seized. ''D\u00e9daigneuse'' was later purchased into the Royal Navy as HMS ''Dedaigneuse''.{{r|\"JW3:136\"}} Shortly afterwards, Cooke captured the Spanish ship ''Carlotta'' and the French [[privateer]] ''G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Brune'' in the same area.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15412|page=1203|date=29 September 1801}}</ref>\n\n==Trafalgar==\n[[File:Trafalgar aufstellung.jpg|thumb|Battle of Trafalgar]]\nWith the [[Peace of Amiens]], Cooke briefly retired on half-pay before being recalled to the fleet at the outbreak of the [[Napoleonic Wars]] in 1803. Cooke was requested as flag captain by Admiral [[William Young (1751\u20131821)|Sir William Young]] at [[Plymouth]], but Cooke tactfully refused, instead applying for active service. He received command of {{HMS|Bellerophon|1786|6}} on 25 April 1805. In May, after the large combined French and Spanish fleet, under Admiral [[Pierre-Charles Villeneuve]] escaped from [[Toulon]], beginning the [[Trafalgar Campaign]], Cooke was ordered to join a flying squadron under Vice-Admiral [[Cuthbert Collingwood, 1st Baron Collingwood|Cuthbert Collingwood]]. The squadron arrived off [[Cadiz]] on 9 June and Collingwood detached ''Bellerophon'' and three other ships to blockade [[Cartagena, Spain|Cartagena]] under Rear-Admiral [[Sir Richard Bickerton, 2nd Baronet|Sir Richard Bickerton]]. When the combined fleet entered Cadiz on 20 August, Collingwood recalled Bickerton's force and mounted a blockade of the port. Collingwood was reinforced with more ships, and was later superseded by Nelson. Cooke was heard to say at this time that \"To be in a general engagement with [[Horatio Nelson|Nelson]] would crown all my military ambition\".{{r|\"ODNB\"}} Nelson had Villeneuve's fleet trapped in Cadiz and was blockading the harbour awaiting their expected attempt to escape.\n\nThe Franco-Spanish fleet escaped Cadiz on 18 October 1805, but was soon chased down by Nelson and brought to battle on 21 October. Nelson formed his fleet into two divisions; the weather column would attack to the north under his direct command and the lee column would operate to the south under the command of Cuthbert Collingwood in {{HMS|Royal Sovereign|1786|6}}. Cooke was stationed fifth in Collingwood's line, and so was one of the first ships engaged in action with the combined fleet. Cooke took the unusual step of informing his first lieutenant [[William Pryce Cumby]] and his master Edward Overton of Nelson's orders, in case he should be killed.{{r|\"CW:47\"}}\n\n''Bellerophon'' was soon closely engaged with the French, breaking through the enemy line and closing with [[French ship Aigle (1800)|''Aigle'']]. As with the other French ships in the fleet, ''Aigle's'' rigging and mastheads were occupied by musketeers and grenadiers, who kept up a steady fire on ''Bellerophon'' and took a heavy toll of sailors exposed on the British ship's deck. Much of the fire was directed at the quarterdeck, where Cooke, Cumby and Overton stood. Cumby noted with surprise that Cooke was still wearing his uniform coat, which sported epaulettes that marked him out as the ship's captain to French snipers. Cooke had forgotten to remove the epaulettes and recognised the danger they represented, but replied \"It is too late to take them off. I see my situation, but I will die like a man\".{{r|\"CW:48\"}}\n[[File:Situation of the Bellerophon at the moment of the death of her gallant commander Captn. Cooke.jpg|left|thumb|alt=Coloured print of a naval battle between sailing ships. Four ships seen stern on in the right of the picture, obscured by clouds of smoke, a fifth ship seen bow on in the left.|''Situation of the Bellerophon at the moment of the death of her gallant commander Captn. Cooke'', early-nineteenth century aquatint by [[Thomas Whitcombe]], showing the ''Bellerophon'' surrounded by enemy ships at the moment of Cooke's death]]\nAs the action continued, the Captain Pierre-Paul Gour\u00e8ge of ''Aigle'' ordered his crew to board and seize ''Bellerophon'', hoping to use their superiority of numbers to overwhelm the British crew. Cooke sent Cumby below to make sure that the lower-deck guns continued to fire into the French ship as the battle continued overhead, and threw himself at the French sailors pouring onto ''Bellerophon's'' quarterdeck, shooting an enemy officer dead and engaging in hand-to-hand combat with the men behind him.{{r|\"CW:48\"}} Within minutes Cumby had returned to the deck with reinforcements from below, passing the mortally wounded Overton on the ladder. The badly wounded ship's quartermaster was also present, and he informed Cumby that Cooke had fallen in the melee.{{r|\"JW4:52\"}} Cumby's charge cleared the French from the deck of ''Bellerophon'', and he found Cooke dead on the quarterdeck, two [[musket]] balls lodged in his chest. Cooke's last words had been \"Let me lie quietly a minute. Tell Lieutenant Cumby never to strike.\"{{r|\"CW:48\"}}\n\nCumby took charge of the battered ''Bellerophon'', directing her fire into ''Aigle'' and ultimately forcing the French ship's surrender after the arrival of other British vessels. ''Bellerophon'' had suffered grievously, losing 27 dead and 127 wounded.{{r|\"JW4:52\"}} Although ''Aigle'' was lost in the chaotic storm which followed the battle, ''Bellerophon'' survived, primarily due to Cumby's leadership. He was later promoted to post captain for his services in the action.{{r|\"CW:52\"}} Cooke's body was [[buried at sea]] the day after the battle with the other fatal casualties from ''Bellerophon''.{{r|\"ODNB\"}}\n\n==Family and legacy==\n[[File:Tomb of Horatio Nelson on Saint-Paul Cathedral.jpg|thumb|Tribute to Cooke on left in the crypt of St Pauls Cathedral]]\n[[File:St Andrew's Church, Donhead St Andrew 16.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Memorial to Cooke in St{{nbsp}}Andrew's Church, Donhead St{{nbsp}}Andrew, in Wiltshire]]\nCooke's death, as with those of [[George Duff]] and Admiral Nelson himself, was widely mourned in Britain. Cooke's widow Louisa and their eight-year-old daughter, Louisa Charlotte, were given numerous awards and presents, including the gold medal minted for the captains who had fought at the action, and a large silver vase presented by [[Lloyd's Patriotic Fund]]. At least some of the money the family received was spent on a large wall plaque mounted in St Andrew's Church in [[Donhead St Andrew]] in [[Wiltshire]], close to the family home.{{r|\"CW:49\"}} The plaque commemorates Cooke's life and death and also that of his wife. A memorial was also raised to him in [[St Paul's Cathedral]]. Tributes from fellow officers were also forthcoming, including from the future explorer [[John Franklin]], who had served on ''Bellerophon'' at Trafalgar and had said of Cooke that he was \"very gentlemanly and active. I like his appearance very much.\"{{r|\"CW:48\"}} A number of letters that Cooke wrote to his brother prior to Trafalgar are held by the [[National Maritime Museum]].{{r|\"National Archives\"}}\n\nCooke had married Louisa, n\u00e9e Hardy, on 15 June 1790 at [[St Leonard's, Shoreditch]]. Louisa was the fourth daughter of [[Josiah Hardy]], the former Governor of New Jersey, and later consul at Cadiz.{{r|\"NT:95\"}} Louisa died at her home, 9 Montpellier Terrace, [[Montpellier, Cheltenham]], on 5 February 1853 aged 96.{{r|\"LC:Death\"}} The funeral was held at [[St Peter's Church, Leckhampton]], on 11 February 1853, with interment following in the churchyard.{{r|\"LC:Funeral\"}} Louisa Charlotte Cooke, their only child, was born on 26 January 1797 at [[Stoke Damerel]].{{r|\"NT:95\"}} Louisa Charlotte married Abraham John Newenham Devonsher of Kilshanick, County Cork, at Cheltenham, on 9 March 1820.{{r|LCC:Marriage}} She died after a short illness at St. Anne\u2019s, Albion Street, Cheltenham, on 30 April 1871 aged 74.{{r|LCC:Death}} She was interred at Bouncer's Lane Cemetery, [[Prestbury, Gloucestershire|Prestbury]], on 5 May 1871.{{r|\"LCC:Funeral\"}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{refbegin}}\n'''a.''' {{Note label|A|a|none}} A number of sources, including T. A. Heathcote's ''Nelson's Trafalgar Captains and Their Battles'', [[Colin White (historian)|Colin White's]] ''The Trafalgar Captains'' and [[John Knox Laughton|John Knox Laughton's]] entry for Cooke in the ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]]'' give a birth year of 1763 and omit most information about Cooke's early life. Nicholas Tracy's entry in ''Who's Who in Nelson's Navy'' provides fuller coverage of Cooke's early life, and includes a specific baptism date. Cooke's baptism register entry records that he was \"borne {{sic}} 17th February in 4 Tenters\".{{r|\"Baptism\"}} Tenters was then part of [[Tenterground]] at [[Spitalfields]], [[London]]. Furthermore, Cooke's father, Francis, is recorded in the 1762 [[English Land Tax|Land Tax Assessment]] Book for the Parish of Saint Mary, Whitechapel, as residing between [[Alie Street]] and [[Leman Street|Leman Street (West side)]], close to the corner of North and East Tenter streets.{{r|\"Land Tax\"}}{{r|Location of Tenterground}}. At the time, Francis worked as a ledger writer at the nearby [[Navy Pay Office (Royal Navy)|Navy Pay Office]] on [[Broad Street (ward)|Broad Street]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=10292|page=3|date=1 March 1763}}</ref>{{r|Examination}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist\n| colwidth = 25em\n| refs = 33em\n  <ref name=\"JH:45\">[[#CITEREFHenderson1994|Henderson]], p. 45.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"JW1:126\">[[#CITEREFJames2002|James]], Vol. 1, p. 126.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"JW2:80\">[[#CITEREFJames2002|James]], Vol. 2, p. 80.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"JW3:136\">[[#CITEREFJames2002|James]], Vol. 3, p. 136.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"JW4:52\">[[#CITEREFJames2002|James]], Vol. 4, p. 52.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"ODNB\">[[#CITEREFLaughton2004|Laughton]].</ref>\n  <ref name=\"NT:95\">[[#CITEREFTracy2006|Tracy]], p. 95.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"NT:96\">[[#CITEREFTracy2006|Tracy]], p. 96.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"CW:47\">[[#CITEREFWhite2005|White]], p. 47.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"CW:48\">[[#CITEREFWhite2005|White]], p. 48.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"CW:49\">[[#CITEREFWhite2005|White]], p. 49.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"CW:52\">[[#CITEREFWhite2005|White]], p. 52.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"Baptism\">[[#CITEREFBaptism1762|Saint Mary, Whitechapel, Register of Baptisms]]. 1762. p. 85.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"Land Tax\">[[#CITEREFLandTax1762|Saint Mary, Whitechapel, Land Tax Assessment Book]]. 1762. p. 73.</ref>\n  <ref name=\"Location of Tenterground\">Approximate centroid of North-, South-, West-, and East- Tenter Street, and Tenter Passage, in 